b88d7581-f082-45b1-9896-ad0af09483bd,K110-GC,Project Berde - Upcycling in Construction,ACTIVE,AEPW,Philippines,Bulacan; Malolos; Pamarawan,PUBLISHED,"Community Project - PAMARAWAN ISLAND, MALOLOS, BULACAN, PHILIPPINES Pamarawan Island is located in the delta of the Pampanga River, where shrimp farms and a popular fishing port are located. Its waterways are challenged with plastic pollution from the incoming high tides and the lack of proper waste management facilities. As part of Project Berde, GreenAntz will set up a marine litter collection scheme for the Pamarawan Island community. Part of the plastic waste aggregated from the community collection points will be upcycled into Eco Boards that will be made available to the Pamarawan Island community at discounted prices. The community can use the boards for furniture or building materials, enabling them to witness circularity which they supported with their plastic waste collection. 75% of the plastic waste collected will be co-processed for energy recovery, 20% will be used in the production of eco-boards, and around 5% will be integrated in the fabrication of eco-bricks.","The project establishes two eco-board manufacturing press lines in Malolos, Bulacan area in the Philippines with the aim of incrementally collecting and upcycling multilayer packaging, sachets into eco-boards.",,GreenAntz,"[""14.76004300000000000"",""120.80840300000000000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
67a6979c-1465-4b53-b975-3f204611e9a4,K112-GC,EcoWorks Buenaventura,ACTIVE,AEPW,Colombia,Buenaventura,PUBLISHED,"The project includes education in the communities to support sustainable solutions for plastic waste management. Most of the collected plastic will be recycled but where markets do not yet exist in the region, unrecyclable streams will be properly landfilled. The project is expected to complete by year end 2023.",EcoWorks and their partners will collect 900 T of plastic waste from communities upstream of Buenaventura. This is an expansion of an existing project they have within Buenaventura.,,EcoWorks,"[""3.87668900000000000"",""-77.01496300000000000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
e1bb865f-02ff-4bad-9602-5e5f2333a777,X001E,Plastic Cycle,ACTIVE,AEPW,Vietnam,Hanoi,PUBLISHED,"Vietcycle is a for-profit scrap collection and recycling company based in Vietnam whose mission is to help develop a strong recycling industry in Vietnam. It has an existing informal plastic waste collection network in Hanoi (""Hanoi Network""). In 2021, Vietcycle collected 7 KT of plastic waste across 105 collection centers over a span of eight months. The collected plastic waste was sorted at Vietcycle-owned existing waste sorting facilities in Hung Yen, Bac Ninh and Vinh Phuc provinces, and sold to downstream recyclers and craft villages that form part of the Hanoi Network. Plastic waste that could not be further processed was properly disposed of by Recipient. Objectives: Beyond the additional 2KT plastic waste volumes that will be collected, this project will allow AEPW to gain a better understanding of the needs of the Informal Waste Sector, as well as test out the collection capability and extent of stakeholder network for local partner- Vietcycle. Approach In Dec 2022, AEPW signed a funding contract with local partner, Vietcycle, to support its efforts to collect 2KT plastic waste (all types) over a 9 month period. Vietcycle intends to expand its Hanoi collection network by setting up 12 new collection centers, working with more than 200 informal waste collectors (""IWC"") to achieve the targeted collection volume. AEPW will be sponsoring Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) and health insurance for the IWCs involved in the project.",This project aims to expand Vietcycle's plastic waste collection network in Hanoi and in the process uplift the livelihoods of hundreds of informal waste collectors within the network.,,Vietcycle Corporation,"[""21.02194800000000000"",""105.83492500000000000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
32713b97-e4c9-4a4d-b878-8cc74c351b87,J010GC,"Collect, Certify, Circulate",COMPLETED,AEPW,Philippines,Manila,PUBLISHED,"The Philippines is the third largest plastic polluter after China and Indonesia, generating over 2.7 million tonnes of plastic waste annually. 83% of this is mismanaged and 20% (~ 0.75 million metric tonnes) enters the ocean every year. Source: Market study for the Philippines: Plastics Circularity Opportunities and Barriers, World Bank, 2021  PCX aspires to d ? o its part to scale the cleanup of plastic pollution and prevent its further leakage into nature. PCX looks to expand its operations through: (1) growing community aggregation infrastructure programme 'Aling Tindera'; and (2) funding the proper collection and recycling/processing of all plastic waste with environmentally compliant partners. The 'Aling Tindera' network is a branded waste-to-cash programme supporting women micro-entrepreneurs. It targets the collection of post-consumer plastic waste directly from community sources and transports them to pre-vetted processors who have committed to disposal in compliance with the standards of Department of Environment and Natural Resources. Project Objectives The objective of the Project is to collect and recycle/co-process 996 tons of post-consumer plastic waste as part of Recipient?s Plastic Waste Recovery and Processing Programs Approach. The project adopts a 3-prong approach, with the Recipient working with partner organizations that conduct a plastic waste recovery and processing mechanism in collaboration with various partners in the Philippines such as: (a) Aling Tindera Waste-to-Cash Programme Piloted in the City of Manila and currently expanding nationwide, the Aling Tindera Waste-to-Cash Programme is a branded initiative working with women microentrepreneurs in every barangay (i.e. district or ward) that participates in the Programme. (b) Plastic Waste Collection Programme Conducted in collaboration with institutional partners (such as SM Supermalls and SM Cares), the Plastic Waste Collection Program allows individuals to drop off their plastic waste at collection points across selected locations (such as shopping malls and townships) in the Philippines, further reducing the risk that plastic waste leaks into the environment. (c) Waste management organizations (aggregators, pre-processors and processors) who recover and process plastic such that these plastics do not end up in landfills or the environment. (collectively, ""Plastic Waste Recovery and Processing Programs"").","PCX's Community Collection Programs provide households and communities with an environmental plastic waste diversion program that benefits communities including livelihoods, infrastructure, and empowerment of women.",,PCX Singapore Pte Ltd Investment,"[""14.63778800000000000"",""121.03478700000000000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
027ef6f0-0439-49bc-9f3d-990007fee71a,K104,Minnesota Recycling Plant,ACTIVE,AEPW,United States,"Rogers, Minnesota",PUBLISHED,"Only 4% of more than 14 billion pounds of flexible packaging film used each year in North America is recycled. Myplas' first plant in the USA in Rogers, Minnesota has one line manufacturing food grade HDPE film PCR using milk containers as the feedstock and other lines produce non-food grade film PCR from a variety of post-use films, largely post-commercial.   Project Objective Install 2 production lines to produce PCR with a capacity of 20 KT/year, expanding to 4 lines with a capacity of 40-50 KT/year by 2025 Divert plastic waste from landfills Attract potential members from the local food and agricultural sector circularity coalition MBOLD (MNCs with headquarters in Minnesota) who are shareholders in Myplas Approach Myplas is an experienced South African recycler entering the US market in partnership with MBOLD and AEPW member Charter Next Generation. After completion of the first facility in Minnesota, they look to replicate with other facilities in North America. The Rogers, Minnesota facility started up in 3Q23.","A  USD project to build a film recycling plant in Minnesota under Myplas, a plastic recycler from Cape Town, South Africa. AEPW has provided a  loan.",,Myplas Recycling Inc,"[""45.20000500000000000"",""-93.53056900000000000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
b687fb4e-3b1a-46e1-b6cf-a9bea341476f,007,Plastic Data Challenge-baseline data in Udaipur,COMPLETED,AEPW,India,Udaipur,ARCHIVED,"The necessary information will be collected quantitatively and qualitatively including primary data collection and desk research for secondary data As part of the Project, the Feasibility Study will be conducted in Udaipur, India. Deliverables provided under the Feasibility Study will be submitted to AEPW in Microsoft Excel format. The primary data collection for municipal solid waste generation, management and leakages will be captured by conducting field surveys by adapting the so-called waste wise city tool (WaCT) with additional focus on plastic waste in local contexts. When looking at city assessment tools the WacT developed by UNHabitat including plastic waste assessments fits the criteria for part of the ISWM assessment. Along with quantitative surveys, focus group discussions and key informant interviews will be conducted with waste workers and key stakeholders respectively. Datasets will be developed in a format (a) to perform plastic pollution hot spotting, and (b) in collaboration with The Circulative Initiative and AEPW such that it is suitable for ingestion into PRISM or that which can be utilized for further data modelling purposes.  ",The aim of the Project is to provide a rationale for a methodological and sampling approach that will meaningfully improve the available data for the chosen geography and prioritize areas where direct data collection can be conducted on the ground.,,TCI,"[""24.60046000000000000"",""73.70452400000000000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
6ccb55cc-d423-4ba6-bd22-fb0a71cbcb97,B005,Project Stop,COMPLETED,AEPW,Indonesia,"Jembrana, Bali",PUBLISHED,"Project STOP in Jembrana, Indonesia, builds on the STOP model previously deployed in the cities of Muncar and Pasaruwan (Java). The model focuses on fostering strong local government and community engagement for the development of an integrated waste system for a rural community, which has previously had limited waste collection and handling infrastructure. The initiative will help residents rid their waste as well as prevent thousands of tons of plastic waste from leaking into the environment, as well as create 100 local jobs for the community.  The project will serve 160,000 residents in Jembrana and Negara--empowering the local community to collect, sort, and sell their own waste. This initiative, in partnership with Project STOP, provides a self-sufficient system which will prevent 2,200 tons of plastic waste from leaking into the environment every year, and collect and process a total of 18,000 tons of waste a year.  The Jembrana Project is a 'zero plastic leakage' program - positioned as a ""system-enabler"" - in which a team of experts in waste management, recycling, financing and education help a city design and implement a waste management system in which all households and institutions benefit from collection. Project Objective: By applying the STOP model, the project aims to: Provide an effective waste collection service in a mid-sized city which previously had no waste management system in place Increase community engagement and education by providing needed resources to change the communities point of view on the importance of continued waste management Sort and collect valuable plastic waste stream for future recycling and re-use. Approach: Conducting waste studies and social mapping to scope and design project Support and training for local partners, government agencies and community institutions Community behaviour change, outreach and training Brokering to recycling off-takers Clean-up of plastic waste accumulation hotspots.","The project builds on the STOP model previously deployed in Muncar and Pasaruwan (Java), fostering strong local government and community engagement to develop an integrated waste system.",,Project STOP,"[""-8.32334400000000000"",""114.66679400000000000""]",ACTUAL,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
98908ebd-7ef8-42df-8b18-19060f7b6d7a,J021,CirculaMare,PIPELINE,AEPW,Croatia,Europe & North Africa,ARCHIVED,"Background The Mediterranean is home to 450 M people, with an additional annual influx of 340 M tourists per year. 24 M tons of plastic waste are generated in the region every year and the low quality and capacity of waste management system in many cities leads to significant plastic waste leakage and low recycling rates. As a consequence, the Mediterranean is one of the most polluted seas in the world, with an estimated 570,000 tons of plastic waste leakage each year, impacting the health of the marine and coastal. Project Objective The project aims to: Identify solutions to manage 50kt/yr of plastics Strengthen institutional capacity and strategies in respect of the management of plastic waste Identify needed plastic waste management infrastructure and strengthen markets for plastic waste products Countries in consideration include Serbia, Greece, Turkey, Kosovo, North Macedonia & Western Balkans, Algeria, Albania, Egypt & Algeria. Approach Evaluate the current situation, local initiatives, and alternative improvement strategies to identify pilot projects addressing different aspects of plastic waste management, including different sectors (tourism, textiles, fisheries) and locations (islands, rivers, coastline). These projects once fully funded and implemented would be expected to provide a toolbox and showcases for waste management, prevention, and financing, adaptable to other locations Analyse the availability of feedstocks and transportation needs for the establishment of centralized waste processing facilities (e.g., large-scale mechanical or chemical recycling) Secure co-funding for the implementation of demonstration projects with for example European Union agencies Establish a regional solution platform for knowledge transfer for private and public sector, involving local and regional stakeholders in order to catalyse co-funding and subsequent replication and scale up",CirculaMare is a programme developed by GIZ to design city-level or archetype specific solutions that address plastic waste pollution in eight countries surrounding the Mediterranean Sea.,,Gesellschaft für Internationale Zusammenarbeit (GIZ),,ESTIMATE,Study,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
2478b84a-c62d-4406-b3ba-ff434702904c,F007,Paving Green Roads,ACTIVE,AEPW,Singapore,Singapore; Thailand,PUBLISHED,"In partnership with Thai PPP, the National University of Singapore, and Chiang Mai University (including association with universities in Indonesia and Vietnam), the Recycled Plastic in Roads research study is examining the implications of integrating waste plastic into asphalt roads in different concentrations and with various polymer types, with attention to issues in microplastic generation and safe implementation. Project Objective: Through this solution that can be used specifically for the waste waste stream that is not eligible for other forms of recycling, the project aims to:  Demonstrate superior quality and mechanical performance when compared to conventional roads Improve and increase the use of plastic waste in the construction of roads Develop knowledge of the material ""recipes"" that will work in different climate conditions Approach Identifying methods to measure microplastics in air due to plastic road use and quantifying the level of microplastic emission, and comparison with conventional roads Quantifying level of fuming due to production, laying and use of plastic roads, and comparison with conventional roads Identifying methods to test for recyclability of plastic roads Demonstrate in the lab the feasibility of recycled plastic roads to future recycling without loss in mechanical properties Testing of environmental, health and safety impacts of this type of application in different geographies  Make the science-based data publicly available, governments might develop specifications for this application in their respective countries","This study is designed to examine the HSE impact of plastic waste recycling integrated into asphalt roads in Singapore, with attention to issues in microplastics and water leaching.",,National University of Singapore and Thai PPP,"[""1.29943000000000000"",""103.77212000000000000""]",ESTIMATE,"Country changed to Singapore from ""Singapore; Thailand",,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
a64b45a4-96ad-41ec-b86b-1fdf067484ac,J211,Nirmal Agra,ACTIVE,AEPW,India,Agra,PUBLISHED,"The Nirmal Agra Project is being implemented in the iconic Indian city of Agra, in partnership with TARA (Technology & Action for Rural Development), to improve waste collection, with a focus on addressing waste aggregation hotspots. This project's purpose is to improve waste collection, especially from hotspots, and the improve the opportunities for recycling, as well as the implementation of a system for data collection associated with the project's mission. A series of small-scale MRFs suited to the historic city layout are being constructed which will process waste delivered by collection vehicles being procured as part of the project. The system targets aggregation of plastic waste for downstream recycling, enabled by a system for plastic waste data collection. Key to the goals of the project is the reduction of waste leakage and waste volumes at landfills. The project is also looking to enable a community engagement program to support the collection and recycling initiatives. Project Objective The project aims to:  Reduce plastic waste leakage to the Yamuna River by nine (9) KTA  Increase the proportion of waste plastic that is mechanically recycled rather than sent to dumpsites and landfills Develop archetype design for collection, sorting and digital solutions which may also be applicable to other cities Approach Phase 1  Collection of plastic from hotspots Set-up and operationalisation of 4 mini-materials recovery facilities (MRFs) Set-up and operationalisation of 2 processing units Initiation of behavioural change campaign Use of digital tools to track collection volumes to optimize collection design and costs Phase 2 Set-up and operationalization of the remaining 8 mini-MRFs and recovery of 7 KTA of plastic for higher value recycling","The Nirmal Agra Project is being implemented in the iconic Indian city of Agra to improve waste collection, with a focus on addressing waste aggregation hotspots.",,TARA,"[""27.20448600000000000"",""78.01646500000000000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
ccf78b84-175f-41ad-a9c0-7a4eea0a49b1,K009,LoveRe,ACTIVE,AEPW,China,Chengdu; Xian; Shanghai,PUBLISHED,"The project with LoveRe involves the installation of 3,000 internet-connected Smart Sorting/Recycling Machines (SSRMs), where consumers can deposit plastic waste by connecting via their WeChat account. The SSRMs are to be located at various strategic points across the cities of Chengdu and Xi'An, including residential districts, commercial supermarkets, and office buildings, with 24/7 availability. With this ""Internet + Recycle"" business model an improvement in recovery of recyclables from 15% to 35% is targeted. Project Objective: The project aims to:  Gain achievement of commercial viable operations, collection of low value flexibles, and improvement in city recycling rates to 35% Enable profitable collection of low value flexibles which today are discarded and end up in landfill Approach Installation and operation of 3000 reverse vending machines in two Chinese cities of Chengdu and Xi'an Start commercial operation in Chengdu and ramp-up vending machines production in mid 2021 Encourage local community to utilize the reverse vending machines via a community education program and WeChat credits Placing Smart Sorting/Recycling Machines (SSRMs) in highly touristed cities to drive up-take ","The LoveRe Project supports the establishment of an Internet + Recycle business in Chengdu and Xian, improving recycling rate from 15% to 35%, and promote proper sustainable behaviours.",,,"[""30.59786200000000000"",""104.05905000000000000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
d6c0b786-7182-42cc-9e3d-bcbd6d8aa6ac,A003B,GIRO,ACTIVE,AEPW,Argentina,Olavarría,PUBLISHED,"The GIRO Argentina project will be implemented in the city of Olavarría (115 K inhabitants, approx. 350km from Buenos Aires) and seeks to replicate a successful pilot project by DelTerra in Barrio 31 district, Buenos Aires, from an informal/slum setting into a formalized settlement. In Barrio 31, the team has worked with local cooperatives to improve the segregation of waste and delivery to collection points, and improved the efficiency of operation at the sorting lines.  Olavarría represents a more formalized settlement, and intent is to adapt and scale-up the Barrio 31 solution.  Project Objective Through adapting the Barrio 31 model to a full Argentinian municipality, the project aims to: Demonstrate community benefit resulting in an additional 2 kt/yr. of avoided leakage Replicate and scale-up project to other communities Approach The 3-year project is divided in three phases: Preparation, involving diagnostics and pilot design Pilot in one area in Olavarría Scaling to the entire city, ensuring sustainability and full hand-over to the municipality","The GIRO Argentina project is being implemented in the city of Olavarría (115 K inhabitants, approx. 350km from Buenos Aires) to provide improved collection and sortation of household waste.",,DelTerra,"[""-36.89371700000000000"",""-60.32335000000000000""]",ACTUAL,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
929afc02-1227-4609-9257-fb1978dfb7dc,E007,The Circulate Initiative,COMPLETED,AEPW,Singapore,Southeast Asia,PUBLISHED,"The Alliance entered into an agreement with The Circulate Initiative (TCI) in early 2019, providing a grant for the set-up and ongoing operating support of the organisation until the end of 2022. TCI has focused its efforts in two areas: Insights and Incubation. The Insights work of TCI is focused on the development of thought leadership pieces on specific topics related to ending plastic waste in the environment and developing a circular economy of plastic. Project Objectives: Prevent the flow of plastic waste into the world's ocean through the establishment of The Incubation Network (TIN) in joint partnership with SecondMuse, targeted as a catalyst for action and investment in the circular economy Provide support to 80+ ventures and nearly 50 accelerators, incubators and entrepreneurial support organizations (ESOs) across SSA that support programme activities carried out by TIN in 2020 and 2021. Approach Phase 1 Launch of new partnerships for 1 incubation site Provide technical assistance to 10 businesses/entrepreneurs/leaders Defining core programmatic strategies for incubation and technical assistance, impact measurement and amplification activities Phase 2 Launch of new partnerships for 2 incubation sites Provide technical assistance to 30 businesses/entrepreneurs/leaders Develop and share impact metrics and methodologies addressing ocean plastic reduction to key stakeholders Phase 3 Launch of new partnerships for 2 incubation sites Provide technical assistance to 75 businesses/entrepreneurs/leaders Refine and share impact methodology/framework addressing ocean plastics with donors, businesses and investors",The Circulate Initiative (TCI) implements a series of incubation and venture building programs supporting small to mid-size start-ups with solutions to address the plastic waste challenge.,,The Incubation Network,"[""1.29790240495635920"",""103.78745539536101000""]",ESTIMATE,"Country changed to Singapore from ""India; Indonesia; Philippines; Thailand; Vietnam",,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
0d18f6f1-6335-4eb4-93da-832234a0158f,H006,Changemakers,COMPLETED,AEPW,India,Kolkata,PUBLISHED,"SOCEO is an NGO operating in Germany and India, supported by the Alliance to implement an education program in 60 high schools in the Sunderbans delta and the metropolitan Kolkata region. The project aims to educate and sensitize students and the broader community around the schools about plastic waste challenges and management through action-oriented learning.  The project stretches from Kolkata through the Sundarbans up to the borders of the Sundarbans National Park. The Sundarbans are a crucial ecosystem, which is situated in the world's largest river mouth system containing one of the world's largest mangrove forests with a unique flora and fauna. The combination of rivers and high population makes inadequate waste management a major contributor to river and ocean plastic pollution.  Students being future citizens will play the crucial role in driving the necessary change in behaviour. In the project, they will raise the high relevant and important issue of waste management in their schools, families, with local community members, local governmental institutions and other stakeholders.  Project Objective The project aims to: Collect and correct disposal or recycling of 15 tons of plastic waste Communicate and engage 300,000 community members Develop a comprehensive education program on plastic waste for high schools, including learning activities on plastic waste, waste management, reuse, upcycling and reduction of plastic waste  Approach Preparation of Offline and Online TLAM (Teaching, Learning and Activity Manuals) i.e study materials for students Assessment of local area waste management by students Education of students through action-learning activities, workshops, clean-ups and games to reduce plastic waste Collection of plastic waste in local household and school waste Collected waste to be handed over to recycling company for analysis Findings and learnings prepared and share with students, local communities and decision markers",The Changemakers is a high school education program in the Suburbans and metropolitan Kolkata region. Students and the community are educated about plastic waste challenges and management.,,SOCEO,"[""22.47355700000000000"",""88.37069400000000000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
d6e56bd9-51bb-4fe3-b532-4c3b5d69aef0,B020,Bersih Indonesia: Eliminasi Sampah Plastik,ACTIVE,AEPW,Indonesia,Java,PUBLISHED,"Indonesia suffers from a substantial lack of organized waste management; the Bersih project was conceived as an evolution of the Project STOP initiatives, including the Alliance-funded Jembrana project. The project focuses on introducing large scale and economically optimized collection service operated by the municipality, and paid for through household collection fees and value capture from sale of recovered recyclable materials.  Project Objective As one of the largest solid waste management projects ever undertaken, the project aims to: Demonstrate a viable approach to waste management collection  Prevent leakage of 140kt/yr across 3 large scale regencies and 6 million inhabitants Create 3 zero plastic waste cities by 2025 Approach Feasibility study conducted to select 3 regencies with Java, taking into consideration leakage levels, government and community preferences, viability of implementation, location of current or future supporting infrastructure and the ability to complement other AEPW projects. Project implementation partners are Systemiq, undertaking project preparation, system design, government engagement, and behavior change campaign, and Mott MacDonald apporting as PMO to oversee procurement and construction. First phase of the project focuses on the regency of Malang, piloting the detailed approach and seeking to catalyse co-financing for this and the subsequent two phases. Intended waste management system involves 5 transfer stations and 5 MRFs with locations optimized by linear programing (supported by Eurodecision). The market development and offtake of recyclable products will be managed by Global Plastics Trading, selected by the Alliance as a project partner through competitive bidding.","The Bersih Indonesia flagship programme targets the implementation of a large-scale, regency-wide integrated waste management system in three regencies on the island of Java.",,Systemiq,"[""-7.97254700000000000"",""112.63423600000000000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
8ebe3b09-2743-4690-b235-f641bf8dd73d,Z004,Basisa Bazaruto,ACTIVE,AEPW,Mozambique,Bazaruto,PUBLISHED,"The Basisa Bazaruto means clean Bazaruto, referring to a project to restore and protect the marine environment at Bazaruto Archipelago National Park, Mozambique. With a population of only 5000, the plastic waste issue is primarily due to litter left behind by tourists and from plastic in the ocean washed up on the beaches, threatening the beauty of the habitat and the 2000 marine species living there, including the last viable population of dugongs in the Western Indian Ocean.   Project Objective Through an education program for both local citizens and park tourists, the project aims to: Improve the beauty of the marine habitat Increase awareness for responsible use of plastic Demonstrate an approach that will catalyse similar efforts across other African national parks Approach Support the employment and training of 50+ waste collectors amongst island residents and setting up waste collection points across the four islands Collected waste will be transported to a newly established MRF facility on the mainland for sorting and recycling or proper disposal of non-recyclable materials Provide ongoing education and awareness campaigns for the local public and park visitors Showcase solutions to attract catalysing capital and how Basisa Bazaruto can be replicated in other locations","This project restores and protects the marine environment by collecting, sorting, and aggregating plastic waste in the Bazaruto Archipelago National Park in Mozambique.",,African Parks,"[""-21.55345500000000000"",""35.18186900000000000""]",ACTUAL,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
b6e99b7f-59c3-4be4-8237-599e45dd0e21,G002,CURB: Clean UnHas River Bound,ACTIVE,AEPW,Indonesia,Sulawesi,PUBLISHED,"Since 1973, Universitas Hasanuddin's Student Study Service program (in Indonesia: Kuliah Kerja Nyata or KKN) has been integrated into the higher education curriculum for Indonesian universities, and has became one of higher education's three-fold responsibilities alongside teaching and conducting research. Through the KKN program, students are required to broaden and share their knowledge and help local people to improve their lives and motivate them towards self-development.  The project is located in South Sulawesi, Indonesia, around three rivers surrounded by 4 million inhabitants. The Maros, Cenrana and Kariango rivers, flowing into the seas (Makassar Strait and Bone Strait), have been identified as some of the main marine debris contributors in Indonesia. Project Objective Alongside the Indonesian student community of University Hasanuddin and their KKN program, the project aims to: Address the plastic waste leakage in the environment by installing waste traps on three rivers Build micro collection and sorting facilities to deal with trash collected  Educate local communities in the responsible use and disposal of plastic Approach Utilize the Kuliah Kerja Nyata (KKN) student service academy program of University of Hasanuddin to: Establish local government support at levels of regency/city and district  Develop and install demonstration scale infrastructure to include transfer storage, segregation, washing, and composting facilities Progress community training across 8 districts within the regency/city to facilitate plastic waste processing, cleaning, and sorting In addition to the University of Hasanuddin, project partners include:  The Marine Plastic Research Group of the Faculty of Marine Science and Fisheries, Universitas Hasanuddin Local governments of Bone, Pinrang and Makassar Regencies Local Waste bank: Bank Sampah Plastic recycler: ADUPI and Asosiasi Sampah Indonesia Organic waste processing: Green Indonesia Foundation (GIF) NGO: Waste-to-Value Centre (supports South Sulawesi waste network, business model analysis and development)","Clean UnHas River Bound project is based on a Universitas Hasanuddin program - Student Study Service, linking academic study with practical experience of community service.",,Universitas Hasanuddin,"[""-3.66879900000000000"",""119.97405300000000000""]",ACTUAL,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
b7ba35a9-0ecd-48c6-9c31-e3c0863393c2,A003A,Rethinking Recycling - Indonesia,COMPLETED,AEPW,Indonesia,Bali,PUBLISHED,"Under the Rethinking Recycling initiative of Delterra, the Rethinking Recycling Academy is being implemented in a series of villages in the vicinity of Denpasar, Bali. The program targets improved household waste segregation and plastic waste recovery, through an integrated system of behaviour change programs, collection services, and sorting centres that handle the full post-consumer waste stream, including all plastics. The Alliance is funding the development of the Academy curriculum and roll-out, while MRF improvements are funded by other partners. Known as The Academy, this project supports the establishment of a formalized learning centre to educate MRF managers and foremen, as well as essential community waste representatives.  The program works to maximize material recovery upstream, through an integrated system of behavior change programs, collection services, and sorting centers that handle the full post-consumer waste stream, including all plastics.  Project Objective The project aims to:  Collect 1.5KTA of plastic waste from 6 communities Sort and sell 1KTA of plastic waste to recyclers Upgrade of infrastructure, operational procedures and collection systems Approach Phase 1 Wave 1 villages Roll out introduction modules and operational modules in cohort 1 villages Launch MSW characterization in Ubung Kaja village Upgrade MRF in Kesiman, Pemogan and Ubung Kaja Preparation for souce sperated collection system roll-out in full villages of Kesiman, Pemogan and Ubang Kaja Evaluate behaviour change initiatives Phase 2 Wave 2 villages Preparation for souce sperated collection system roll-out in pilot villages if Tegal Kertha, Pemecutan Kaja and Sanur Kauh Begin operation of MRF for Sanur Kauh, Pemecutan Kaja and Tegal Kertha","Maximising upstream material recovery through an integrated system of behavior change programmes, collection services, and sorting centers that handle the full post-consumer waste stream.",,DelTerra,"[""-8.67039585247173500"",""115.24051288006189000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
2474a203-6400-48eb-a19c-72c440011be2,J004,Circulaire Abidjan,ACTIVE,AEPW,Côte d'Ivoire,Abidjan,PUBLISHED,"The Circulaire Abidjan project is located in the coastal city of Abidjan, on the southern Atlantic coast of Ivory Coast, in West Africa. It has been identified as a marine litter hotspot, with a population of approximately 5.3 million inhabitants.  Coliba Africa is an African start-up company from Abidjan, currently collecting 1.2 KTA of plastic waste, most of which is PET sent as bales for export through use of collection containers and drop off points, supported by education and mobile technology to pay for waste collected. Coliba Africa applied through the Allliance's Plastic Waste Free Cities RFP for support to expand this model, with the ambition to further scale and replicate to other West African countries and to drive the development of a local circular economy of plastics.  The project involves establishment of collection bins at Shell and Total petrol stations, and more than 60 collection containers where residents and informal sector workers can deposit their plastics. Collected plastic waste is baled and transferred to the Coliba plant where new sorting, washing, and flaking lines will be installed, resulting in high quality recycled plastic sold to customers in Africa and Europe. Project Objective The project aims to: Expand the existing collection and recycling of plastic waste from 1.2kt/yr to 14 kt/yr Increase the ability to pay for collection of an increasing amount of plastic waste  Provide a foundation for further scaling and replication into other African countries  Approach The project scope comprises of: Increasing the plastic waste collected by deploying an additional 50 collection boxes in TotalEnergies and Shell service stations and 60 drop-off points in the city of Abidjan Installing a recycling plant to scale up the recycling capacity from 1.2KTA to 14KTA of PCR: 7KTA of PETwaste washed and flaked Transitioning the existing recycling plant to process 5KTA PP & HDPE in support of broadening Coliba Africa's collection and processing of waste plastic beyond PET Enhancing the existing mobile application that connects households and businesses with affiliated waste pickers in Abidjan Developing an educational program ""Protect Your Planet"" to reach 30k students in the local schools of Abidjan","The Coliba Africa project targets improved collection, processing, and sale of rigid plastic waste (PET, HDPE, and PP) in the city of Abidjan.",,Coliba Africa,"[""5.37763262285360400"",""-3.99916454284801300""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
82292b4f-ded5-4e11-86f6-208b6c09535f,K119-GC,Clean ECO,ACTIVE,AEPW,Brazil,"Curitiba, Paraná",PUBLISHED,"Clean Eco is a partner that was created with the objective of strengthening the Group's socio-environmental actions and working with the principles of ESG. The Group's 8th company values the work of the collectors, who are responsible for more than 90% of the recyclable materials in Brazil. Clean Eco has been in operation since January 2023. They are currently processing 300 tonnes per month of all plastic waste types and plan to expand and divert plastics from going to the landfill. The Alliance is providing a grant to fund bailing equipment to optimize Clean Eco's recycling facility and uplift processing capacity by 8.4 LTA (up to 1000 tonnes per month).","The project consists of the acquisition of a new hydraulic press and conveyor belt to de-bottleneck the recipient's current recycling facility in Curitiba, Brazil.",,Clean ECO,"[""-25.44586741979289000"",""-49.27814273861081000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
ecddcc74-03bd-4041-ae3e-3bb86cb852d5,C009,Closing The Loop,ACTIVE,AEPW,Ghana,Accra,PUBLISHED,"ASASE Foundation is an NGO that provides a platform for the empowerment of women by offering seed along with technical and business training to build their own plastic waste reprocessing plant. Phase 1 ASASE is an NGO that provides a platform for the empowerment of women by offering seed money and technical and business training to build their own plastic waste reprocessing plant.   The first plant started operating in Accra, Ghana in January of 2019. The project entails financial and technical support to consolidate the operation of the existing plant, purchase equipment to expand its capacity, and to conduct analysis to develop business models that allow continuous operation without subsidies.   As part of the program, ETH Zurich (also known as the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology) has joined as an academic partner offering part-time researchers who will conduct environmental analysis and help identify economically sustainable end-markets at larger scale. Phase 2 Phase 2 of the ASASE project directly builds on the Phase 1 as a co-financed project with the European Commission Delegation to Ghana consisting of ""setting-up of new plastic recycling factories and development of a reward-for-recycling scheme in certain communities in Accra, Ghana"". Project Objective Phase1 Consolidate the existing operations of the ""CASH-IT"" plant to optimise utilisation, operational costs, and commercial transactions Scale-up of the processing capacity to 2 kt/yr. (HDPE and LDPE) Diversify the range of applications for recyclates to achieve higher commercial value. Phase2 To build a new plant in the community of Nungua Teshie, with intention of achieving full capacity of 2 kt/yr by Q3 2023 Identify a new location for a third plant, with development planned for 2023 and running at full capacity by 2024. Bring total capacity across all three plants to 6 kt/yr Additionally target training of waste pickers, students/teachers and community resides in waste management best practices.  Approach Phase1 Consolidate the existing operations of the ?CASH-IT? plant, optimising utilisation, operational costs, and commercial transactions Scale-up of the processing capacity to achieve 2 KTA (HDPE and LDPE) through adding a second process line, utilizing a refurbished, second-hand extruder  Validate one or two new end-market applications and expand the range of possible applications for recyclates into products of a higher commercial value Phase 2 Build a new plant in the community of Nungua Teshie with a capacity of 2 KTA, reaching full capacity by Q3 2023 Identify a new location for a third plant, with development planned for 2023 and running at full capacity by 2024 Train waste picker, students/teachers and residents of communities of Accra in applicable waste management best practices","Closing the Loop supports local entrepreneurs from vulnerable communities in Accra, Ghana by channeling the value of plastic waste back to communities through jobs and new income streams.",,ASASE Foundation,"[""5.60371700000000000"",""-0.18696400000000000""]",ACTUAL,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
b636983f-6a7f-4160-8ec8-4d4bd4e678f1,K004,Waste Processing into Resin8,ACTIVE,AEPW,United States,"San Jose, York, Pennsylvania",PUBLISHED,"The Center for Regenerative Design and Collaboration (CRDC) has developed and operates at small scale in Costa Rica and pilot facilities in Pennsylvania, USA, and S. Africa, a process for the conversion of co-mingled, contaminated and hence difficult-to-recycle plastic waste (including materials recovery facility (MRF) residuals and river/ocean-bound plastic) into a high-value, lightweight aggregate, under their trade name RESIN8. This high-value aggregate is utilized as a concrete modifier in structural and non-structural concrete products. The product enables enhanced performance characteristics in concrete including strength, weight, fire resistance, and thermal resistance and has been used extensively to date in construction of social housing in a partnership with Habitat for Humanity, high end housing, and other construction projects. The solution also has the potential to mitigate the environmental impact of over-exploitation of riverbeds and increasing shortage of construction quality sand.  Project Objective The project aims to: Demonstrate technical and economic viability of the CRDC solution and expand market applications through rull commercial scale-up of the operations in Costa Rica Construct 2 new plants to process a total of 24kt/yr of hard-to-recycle, co-mingled and contaminated plastic waste into an environmentally beneficial concrete additive for use in structural and non-structural cement Provide funding to support market development efforts to help realise CRDC's 5-year vision of building plants to consume 2+ million tons per annum of the most difficult to recycle plastic waste  Approach Expand the existing CRDC RESIN8 plant in Costa Rica from 1 ton/day to a full commercial scale facility (108 tons/day)  Installation the first line of a RESIN8 production plant in York, Pennsylvania in the United States (36 tons/day)  Support product approvals in a range of cement applications Support global marketing and development of the project pipeline global to enable rapid adoption and further replication of the approach","High-value aggregates can be utilized as a concrete modifier in structural and non-structural concrete products, enhancing end-characteristics such as strength, and fire resistance.",,CRDC Global Ltd (Centre for Regenerative Design and Collaboration),"[""39.97551013636715600"",""-76.70713256740860000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
1753817b-47af-4e7a-9b96-595ba1ba5cd3,B006,AVIRAL,COMPLETED,AEPW,India,Haridwar; Rishikesh,PUBLISHED,"The AVIRAL project will pilot the deployment of a comprehensive waste management system in two neighboring cities in the North of India, located along the river Ganga, to be implemented by the Deutsche Gesellschaft fur international Zusammenarbeit (GIZ) as project partner. The two cities, Rishikesh and Haridwar have a combined residential population of only 400,000, but more than 18 million tourists and pilgrims per year. Haridwar hosted the largest Hindu festival (Kumgp Mela) in 2022, expected to attract ~35 million pilgrims and tourists. The project aims to build MRF infrastructure to facilitate managing the plastic waste challenges and will provide local awareness training and an exchange of best practices throughout India.   Project Objective Through the implementation of a comprehensive waste management system in an area of high religious significance, the project aims to: Reduce plastic leakage in Haridwar and Rishikesh by 7kt/year Promote the Alliance, GIZ and the opportunities for improvement throughout India Approach The project scope incorporates: Baseline studies of plastic waste streams Capacity building through development of city level plastic waste management action plans, training and knowledge exchange for municipal officials Pilot projects on source segregation, the setup of two MRFs (one in each city), and training for waste generators, the informal sector and enterprises A grand challenge for innovative technology and business models for recycling solutions, and facilitation of cross-learnings between R&D institutions An event guide for plastic waste management and outreach to targeted groups for improved awareness and engagement","AVIRAL means continuous in Hindi, reflecting a project to provide continuous and comprehensive waste management system in two neighboring pilgrim cities in the north of India.",,Aviral GIZ,"[""29.94569100000000000"",""78.16424800000000000""]",ACTUAL,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
cb60c0e1-3bf9-4a9c-8322-adc39e767d18,N001,Litterati,COMPLETED,AEPW,United States,Global,PUBLISHED,"Litterati is a mobile app which is designed to engage the public, company employees, communities, and students in cleaning up litter in their environment, and in doing so, creating identifying images of each piece of waste in real time, providing high-value data to Cities, Brands and the global community.  The project serves to enhance the capability and usage of the Litterati app in key dimensions specified to magnify the impact of waste management initiatives.  Project Objective With a target of more than one million users, the project aims to: Improve and expand ""Machine-Learning"" models to better characterise litter in the environment Integrate location and mapping with litter recognition features will help to provide insights into recycling opportunities at any given location Increase engagement through gamification features to reward and increase the user communities of the mobile app, reaching one million users Develop and test a ""Minimum Viable Product"" to compensate informal waste picker communities to expand their range of plastic waste type collected. Approach Phase 1  Gamification Introduction of two gamification elements to the mobile app to increase user engagement and retention Design elements to encourage rewards and social engagement/interaction Phase 2 Machine Learning Deployment of machine learning for at least 500 classes of litter in categories of waste Deployment of recyclability feedback feature in app Related to a specific geography with a discrete set of users for beta testing Current Highlight The Alliance project with Litterati has focuses on delivering four capabilities to extend Litterati's offering and impact - improving and expanding image recognition models, developing educational components for schools, developing behavior-based gamification features, and piloting in the developing world as a tool for communities.  This video summarizes this fourth element: applying the Litterati app as both a measurement and an engagement tool in two communities in Kerala, India in combination with school and family education programs facilitated through a community liaison. The program was conducted in partnership with the local NGO Greenworms. The video illustrates the success of the program for the communities, their environment, and for developing leadership competencies through the liaison role itself.","Litterati is a mobile app which is designed to engage the public, communities, and students in recognising and acting on plastic waste in the environment.",,Litterati,"[""37.81593476009561500"",""-122.20494856142848000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
f115193d-65b9-4d03-bcbd-916c9eb9b62c,L011,HolyGrail 2.0,ACTIVE,AEPW,France,Denmark; France; Germany,PUBLISHED,"The Digital Watermarks Initiative HolyGrail 2.0 (HG2.0) follows on from the initial pioneering project HolyGrail 1.0 facilitated by the Ellen MacArthur Foundation (EMF) in 2016-2019 to evaluate different technologies for highly granular and accurate sorting of mixed plastic waste. HG2.0 is facilitated by AIM, the European Brands Association, with more than 120 participants amongst major consumer brands, retailers, convertors, resin producers, packaging companies, recyclers and technology providers, which pursues the adoption of sorting based on digital watermarks, selected for ease of implementation. Digital watermarks (imperceptible 2D and 3D codes the size of a postal stamp either printed or embossed multiple times on plastic articles) will enable identification and association with a wide range of attributes, e.g. full article composition and characteristics, food vs non-food etc.   Project Objective Through adopting digital watermarks read by NIR scannners linked to automated sorting equipment, the project aims to: Prove the commercial viability of digital watermarking technologies, the business model, and strategy for large scale deployment in Europe  Improve recycling rates by 2-3 Mt/yr Improve the traceability of plastic packaging which can guide many aspects of packaging design, waste management and EPR systems Approach Phase 2 HG2.0 brand-owners/retailers have supplied different light-weight plastic or composite/coated cardboard packaging articles test-samples with a 2D printed label or 3D embossment utilising Digimarc Platform technology The ability to accurately detect and hence sort 250+ articles was tested at commercial scale in simulated compacted, deformed and contaminated states, representative of typical consumer recycling in two test locations:  Amager Resource Center (MRF), Copenhagen have completed testing with significant prototype industrial scale digital-water mark detection developed by Pellenc ST  Borealis/TOMRA plant (PRF) at Lahnstein, Germany are testing prototype industrial scale DW detection developed by TOMRA  Phase 3 Brand-owners/retailers will implement digital watermarking on ~10 SKU (Stock-Keeping Unit) each, which will enable functional performance to be demonstrated on post-consumer waste at full commercial scale at six sorting/recycling sites across Germany, France The demonstrations will be showcased with a view to driving subsequent adoption across Europe",HolyGrail 2.0's objective is to assess the technical and economic viability of digital watermarks and their positive impact on increasing the recycling of plastic packaging.,,AIM (European Brands Association),"[""48.91591492322491000"",""2.31529399808574170""]",ESTIMATE,"Country changed to France from ""Denmark; France; Germany",,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
87904e29-ca05-43b0-9df1-fa28dbacc4bd,B001B,Rayong Less-Waste,ACTIVE,AEPW,Thailand,Rayong,PUBLISHED,"The Federation of Thai Industry (FTI) and the Thai Public Private Partnership for Plastics (Thai PPP) are designing and deploying a scalable model for a recyclables collection and sorting system for up to 60 villages across Rayong Province, focused on the recovery of plastic waste. The system is based on the successful model deployed in the village of Wang Wa, a municipality of 2,100 inhabitants, where monthly residual waste tonnage sent to landfill has been reduced from 60 to 4 tons. A national cross-value chain collaboration platform, Thai PPP (""Thailand Public-Private Partnership for Plastic""), led by the Federation of Thai Industry (FTI) and the Thailand Business Council for Sustainable Development (TBCSD), has been set up with local industry and government support to find solutions and build a circular plastic economy focusing on infrastructure improvement, innovation, and education. Project Objective The project aims to: Roll out the ""Wang Wa Model"" to 628 communities in 68 municipalities Affect behavioural change which will divert waste from landfills and the environment Provide training on the utilization of the ""Wang Wa Model"" to 230 schools in 68 municipalities Approach The project will build on the activities already completed in Wang Wa, document them, and roll them out to other communities in Rayong Province. It will focus on: Educating community members in sorting waste, enabling the creation of value from plastics via aggregation and repurposing into alternative products Enrolling community leaders and networks to lead the changes and implementation from within D eveloping education materials, tools and coaching programs",The FTI and the Thai PPP are designing and deploying a scalable model for a recyclables collection and sorting system for up to 60 villages across Rayong Province.,,Federation Thai Industry Plastic Club,"[""12.68139600000000000"",""101.28162600000000000""]",ACTUAL,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
2d4adf78-badc-41f9-8f1a-0f5e507a5c9f,B016,Zero Plastic Waste Island,COMPLETED,AEPW,Thailand,Koh Samet,PUBLISHED,"The project is for the creation of a closed island recycling system for plastic waste generated on the island of Koh Samet in the Gulf of Thailand via a pyrolysis chemical recycling unit. Plastic waste used as feedstock is currently sent to a dumpsite on the island.  The Zero Plastic Waste Island project aims to create a closed island recycling system for plastic waste generated on in Koh Samet in the Gulf of Thailand via a pyrolysis chemical recycling unit. The project targets recovery of plastic waste streams from households and tourist operators. Project Objective The principal objective of this project is the development of a master plan for small islands where waste is collected (~10tpd ++) as well as the basic infrastructure to support the goals. Approach Phase 1 Comprehensive Island plastic waste mapping and characterization Determine regulation governing feedstock listed and compliance needs Phase 2 Civil Engineering study (Site topography, logistics, utilities access, constructability information - Soil, seismic, topography, flooding etc) Design One World Urban Rig and Capex Emissions, effluent and solids assessment Socio-environmental impact assessment Phase 3 Design framework and valorization scheme Development of monitoring system (e.g. indicators) including a reporting format for measuring the amount of plastic material inflow into the island as well as plastic waste recycling Development of verification system for plastic neutrality of the island by the offset activities in a collaboration with the framework of UNEP's SEA Circular Initiative","On the island of Koh Samet in the Gulf of Thailand, this project is developing a closed island recycling system, via a pyrolysis chemical recycling unit, for plastic waste generated on the island.",,IGES,"[""12.55987642323948000"",""101.45052282625800000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
5e184ad1-641b-4739-929b-a7a2e34da7d9,K008,ParikraM,ACTIVE,AEPW,India,Pondicherry; Ponda; Bangalore; Mussoorie; Naintal; Oulgaret,PUBLISHED,"The ReCity Digital Platform project is a comprehensive approach to develop sustainable solutions for waste processing such that no waste is sent to landfill and instead is diverted to licensed waste processing facilities across the entire fraction.  The project consists of the installation of material recovery facility (MRF) infrastructure in six cities across India, which will be supported by a fully integrated digital platform to provide traceability and optimization in recovery and recycling of at least 13.5 KTA post-consumer plastic waste.  The ReCity Digital Platform project aims to improve waste collection and recycling, combining proven, collection and processing infrastructure, with a digital platform to incentivise and expand collection. The project will also undertake community level education about source segregation and littering across residential, commercial and institutional waste generators. Project Objective The project aims to: Improve the value derived from waste Deploy digital technology to trace and optimize flow of source segregated material from smart address households and property units  Utilise digital technology for facility management of MRFs to ensure efficiency of material handling and operations Build 12 MRFs in 6 cities to improve the efficiency of material sorting, pre-processing and maximize value capture to recover and recycle at least 13.5 KTA of post-consumer plastic waste Approach Educate the community about source segregation and littering across residential, commercial and institutional waste generators Provide additional skill training and equipment to waste workers for effective service delivery Deployment of digital technologies to optimize operations and materials tracing Expand existing collection networks through door to door and community level education and professionalizing waste workers  ",This project aims to develop sustainable solutions for waste processing such that waste is diverted to licensed waste processing facilities across the entire fraction.,,ReCity,"[""27.49213088285775000"",""77.67311557989440000""]",ESTIMATE,Mathura,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
6c75ef2c-04c4-4ab2-a938-16254e9e0d50,C031,Jingsu - Creating Value from Plastic Waste along the Yangtze,ACTIVE,AEPW,China,Suzhou,PUBLISHED,"JINGSU is derived from reducing plastic waste in Suzhou, China. The Chinese river systems are estimated to have a significant impact on the leakage of plastic into the world's oceans. The Yangtze River is claimed to be one of the most significant sources of marine litter, carrying between 25% and 55% of all plastic waste entering the oceans from rivers. Jingmen is a prefecture-level city, located further upstream on the Yangtze River with a population of approximately 3 million inhabitants. While Suzhou is a large city in the downstream section of the Yangtze river, with a population of 10 million people. The project aims to reduce plastic waste along the Yangtze River by promoting sustainable waste management practices and enhancing plastic management infrastructure.  A key focus of the project is to develop and showcase a solution of investing in recycling and strengthening plastic value chains in urban areas to address the growing amount of waste with a circular approach. The project is a feasibility study which will be conducted over a period of 3 months in Suzhou city. Project Objective The project aims to: Set the baseline of uncontrolled plastic waste leakage and plastic waste hotspots along the river.  Monitor and evaluate the impact of plastic waste load within the river body.   Develop a locally usable/useful/viable methodology for plastic waste monitoring in rivers Approach Phase 1 Carry out an assessment of plastic waste hotspots and leakage streams into the Yangtze river in Suzhou: Identifying the key water bodies in the demonstration area, and selecting the representative rivers/branches/water mouth that is appropriate for monitoring Measuring/or estimating the total mass and composition of plastic waste generated, the mass of mismanaged plastic waste and the mass of river-leaked plastic waste Conducting a temporal monitoring campaign of at least 9 measuring events across at minimum 3 months' time Phase 2 Collaborate with the ""Zero Waste City"" Action Plan of Suzhou, introducing the collection and recycling system for ""Low-value Plastic"", especially on Food and Beverage Container (FaBC) in Suzhou city Provide capacity development for municipal officials to improve knowledge and managerial capacities on (plastic) waste management Provide capacity development for the stakeholders along the plastic value chain Developing drop-off points to collect the FoBC from communities and schools, Providing training to the communities and students to raise targeted awareness on plastic waste prevention, reduction and segregation. Develop and optimize a plastic material flow monitoring methodology Establish a digital tracking, monitoring and reporting system for medium- and low-value plastic waste to identify potential opportunities and increase the valorization of these waste streams, with a specific focus on plastic waste generated from the takeaway sector, to close the loop from consumption, collection, transportation to recycling in close coordination with Meituan and other relevant stakeholders","The project aims to reduce plastic waste in the Yangtze River by promoting waste management practices by enhancing plastic waste management infrastructure, and processing plastic waste.",,GIZ,"[""31.29976911322012600"",""120.58024799682416000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
b214142b-5605-472e-8e9f-fbd5069a8459,O001,End Plastic Waste Innovation Platform,ACTIVE,AEPW,Singapore,Global,PUBLISHED,"The Alliance and Plug and Play have created an accelerator program focused on the plastics value chain to identify innovative start-ups that address the challenge of plastic waste in the environment.   The End Plastic Waste Innovation Platform identifies innovative ideas in the following key areas: Collection, management, and sorting of plastic waste Recycling and processing technologies Extraction and value creation from post-recycled plastics Once identified, the startup finalists from each regional hub participate in a 12-week residency programme that helps them fine-tune their pitching and presentation skills, meet industry experts among our member companies, and get valuable access to potential investors through Plug and Play's extensive network. Eventually, 10 start-ups will be selected to present their solution for possible investment opportunities from the Alliance and our member companies.  Project Objective The project aims to:  Identify and foster 10 start-ups capable of contributing materially to the Alliance mission to end plastic waste Deliver 2 pilot investment or project per accelerator program  Approach The project scope includes: Sourcing and vetting the field of leading start-ups to be considered for the program Identifying and on-boarding the Alliance panel of member company experts Selecting Top 20 then final 10 start-ups for the program during a selection day event Conducting 90-day Accelerator Program for and with the final cohort of 10 program start-ups Organising an Expo Day Event to showcase graduating start-ups to members and investors",Partnering with global innovation incubator Plug and Play to establish a sustainability-focused accelerator program for startups from across the plastic value chain around the world.,,Plug and Play,"[""1.29360580059516780"",""103.86038183136091000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
55eee4e7-7006-4dd7-bc6a-38897fcb1b85,A001,Waste Wise Cities Campaign,ACTIVE,AEPW,"Kenya, Ethiopia, India","Kenya, Ethiopia, India",PUBLISHED,"The Alliance is supporting UN Habitat with a grant to enable implementation of their Waste Wise Cities tool in 6 cities, 2 each in Kenya, Ethiopia, and India, leading to the development of investable, city-wide waste management projects for funding by the Alliance or other parties. Project Objective  The project aims to: Decrease generation of waste and foster sustainable consumption and community engagement Improve municipal solid waste collection and controlled management Increase recycling of suitable materials Approach Engage local governments of the target cities for the joint implementation of projects to improve plastic waste management Conduct ground assessment in target cities in Ethiopia and India Support each of the target cities with the necessary organizational and technical assistance to map plastic recovery capacity and facilities Support target cities to develop a Waste Flow Diagram to assess waste flows and quantify plastic leakage Engage key waste stakeholders- including informal sector through workshops to present and discuss drafted project proposals and finalise project proposals based on stakeholder feedback Gather robust and standardized data on existing waste management infrastructure, quantity, quality and composition by applying UN-Habitat's Waste Wise Cities Tool  Identify gaps in the waste management system in Nairobi and Mombasa (Kenya), Addis Ababa and Bahir Dar (Ethiopia), and Mangalore and Thiruvananthapuram (India) Develop project concepts in cooperation with the respective local governments and other partners to improve waste management and close gaps  Submit full-fledged project proposals in alignment with AEPW under the Engaging with Cities expert group","Together with UN Habitat, this project implements their Waste Wise Cities tool in 6 cities in Kenya, Ethiopia and India, developing investable, city-wide waste management projects.",,UN Habitat,,,Study,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
8d0e8305-413e-414e-83ae-6bb207345b8c,B001A,Eco Digiclean Klongtoei,COMPLETED,AEPW,Thailand,Bangkok,PUBLISHED,"A national cross-value chain collaboration platform, Thai PPP (""Thailand Public-Private Partnership for Plastic""), led by the Federation of Thai Industry (FTI) and the Thailand Business Council for Sustainable Development (TBCSD), has been set up with local industry and government support to find solutions and build a circular plastic economy focusing on infrastructure improvement, innovation, and education.  The Alliance to End Plastic Waste is supporting this initiative in 2 cities: Bangkok and Rayong (see ""Rayong less waste project""), together with SCG, Dow and Suez. In central Bangkok, Khlong Toei with a population of ~102,900 people is a district bordered by the Chao Phraya River and contains major port facilities and the site of a major market, the Khlong Toei Market. Despite the slum conditions, it is the best performing district in respect to waste management and reduction planning in Bangkok and therefore offer a good situation to work further to enable greater circularity.  Project Objective Through collecting back models and utilising a digital technology platform, the project aims to: Address consumer behaviour to support circular economy principles to bring materials back into the value chain for a second life in a central district of Bangkok Inform and design waste management policy in Thailand Approach The Thai PPP will: Collaborate with local private organisations to implement 8 drop-off points and 2 aggregation hubs to enable take-back channels of recyclable plastics, integrating them as part of existing infrastructure including informal sectors in big/mega cities Develop a digital app to link the drop-off points with potential off-takers and test the value required to motivate different classes of individuals in Bangkok to bring plastic waste to the recycling drop-off points. This will aid in understanding the behavioral drivers of people to sort, recycle and trade plastic.  This information gathered will support the future design of an integrated waste management system suitable and scalable for Bangkok",The FTI and the Thai PPP target improvement of plastic waste collection system within the low-income district of Klongtoei in Bangkok.,,Federation Thai Industry Plastic Club,"[""13.73002900000000000"",""100.57116800000000000""]",ACTUAL,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
06358421-7d62-42f5-a9fb-3e7463e9867f,J002,Plastic Waste Free Cities Programme,ACTIVE,AEPW,India; Indonesia; Malaysia; Philippines,"India, Philippines, Indonesia, Malaysia",PUBLISHED,"ICLEI The Developing Plastic Waste Free Cities Programme (ICLEI) will work with cities within its network to bring about investment ready, city-wide proposals in two cities in India, and three in South East Asia / East Asia.   Project Objective Guided by 3 over-arching deliverables, the project aims to: Create investment ready projects, consistent with the AEPW's Engaging with Cities RFP requirements, which is available on The Alliance website. Fund and execute initial projects within 5 identified cities Replicate and scale initial projects utilising catalysed capital to pursue implementation of the full Waste Management plan Approach This project is guided by three over-arching deliverables:  Preparation of a waste management plan and project roadmap to select a minimum of five cities throughout South Asia, South-East Asia, and East Asia.   Create investment ready projects, consistent with the AEPW's Engaging with Cities RFP requirements, which is available on The Alliance website. This must also lead to the funding and successful execution of initial projects within the five identified cities. Subsequent replication and scaling of the initial projects utilising catalysed capital to pursue implementation of the full Waste Management plan and project roadmap is the third key objective of the programme.","The programme will work with cities to bring about investment ready, city-wide proposals in two cities in India, and three in South East Asia / East Asia.",,ICLEI,,,Study,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
7620d9c3-0162-41fb-88e8-0a3654a9ce04,O002,Accelerating Creativity & Excellence (ACE) Grant Call,ACTIVE,AEPW,Singapore,Singapore,PUBLISHED,"The Accelerating Creativity & Excellence (ACE) Grant Call is a joint call with Singapore's Nanyang Technology University (NTU) - one of the top 50 universities in the world - to their extended academic community, seeking to support potential high impact research into advanced technologies and behavioural and social science relevant to ending plastic waste. Sustainability is a strategic driver for NTU's development; NTU will provide 50% of the grant and and will reach out to draw the creativity, capability and expertise of senior professors, young researchers, and post-doctorates supported by world-class R&D infrastructure and facilities.  The grants awarded are focusing on the strategic pillars of innovation and education to end plastic waste in the environment.   Project Objectives The NTU-AEPW Grant Call is focused on contributing to end plastic waste through innovation in two key themes: (1) Advanced Technologies, including AI and data science; (2) Behavioural and Social Aspects.   Approach A joint NTU-AEPW Steering committee has selected and continues to steer and monitor the successful proposals, leveraging member companies' expertise and interest where appropriate and relevant.  Success versus the objectives will be measured by follow-up investment, number of projects, growth, and and delivery of the graduating start-ups by the Alliance, member companies and potentially external investors.",The NTU Grant Call is a joint Accelerating Creativity & Excellence (ACE) Grant Call to the academic community of Nanyang Technology University (NTU) - one of the top 50 universities in the world.,,Nanyang Technological University,"[""1.34885625857858480"",""103.68447011529452000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
eada1dc5-c8b4-4a71-860b-9382cdee0d01,J223-GC,Rigid Plastic PET Recycling,ACTIVE,AEPW,Philippines,Bulacan,PUBLISHED,"The aim of the project is to collect post-consumer PET bottles through junkshops and Material Recovery Facilities (MRFs), managed by Local Government Units (LGUs) from different areas around Bulacan. The collected bottles shall be converted into recycled PET (rPET) flakes that can be used as feedstock for rPET products. The rPET flakes are sent to other recycling partners in Vietnam that specialize in the production of polyester staple fiber.",A joint project between Plastic Credit Exchange and Royal Rainbow Recycling Inc. to collect and convert PET waste into flakes that can be used as recycled feedstock in new PET products.,,Plastic Credit Exchange (PCX),"[""14.81378790340152600"",""121.03831901139830000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
c7ec6927-6775-446c-a8b7-e18687f87517,N005,Ocean Stewards,COMPLETED,AEPW,Indonesia,Bali,PUBLISHED,"In 2019, before the Covid-19 pandemic, Recipient had engaged with 20 schools in Bali Indonesia to provide basic training on plastic waste and plastic collection that involved about 5000 children. An internal assessment of the program surfaced an opportunity to create a more substantial and scalable educational model using digital education in addition to face-to-face learning. The focus will be on environmental education, waste management practices, recycling and circular economy, paired with the Recipient's ecosystem to create long-lasting behaviour change and impact.   The program aims to build a scalable and proven educational model to promote behaviour change through educating children and their families in the sustainable use of plastic and creating value for plastic waste through integration with the Recipient's ecosystem for plastic collection, piloted in 20 schools in Bali, Indonesia. Project Objective The objective is to build a scalable, multi-lingual and financially effective educational model to promote behaviour change by creating value from plastic, to be piloted in 20 schools in Bali to provide:  Educational tools and curriculum to motivate future ocean ambassadors  Developing a digital distribution and training mechanism for schools and educators to access the educational material through the Plastic Bank mobile platform  Approach The pilot project will comprise six work streams:   Curriculum development and translation to include training resources for educators and translating curriculum materials from English into Bahasa.   Creation of a digital toolbox to include developing online courses for educators and adapting online courses into the Plastic Bank online application.  Year-long pilot project across 20 schools, reaching 5000 students. This will include onboarding schools, setting up plastic collection points, facilitating logistics, rolling-out the learning activities and the implementation of plastic collection.  Evaluation to include reporting on qualitive and quantitative outcomes and providing learnings and recommendations to scale-up globally. Integration of the schools into the Plastic Bank eco-system for plastic collection creating value from the plastic used by the participating families Provide the digital distribution and training mechanism for schools and educators to access the educational material through the Plastic Bank mobile platform","The ambition behind the Plastic Bank Global Education Program is to build a scalable and proven educational model to create value from plastic to be piloted in 20 schools in Bali, Indonesia.",,Plastic Bank,"[""-8.66849265931384500"",""115.19046167405783000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
624376a3-d7d1-4925-9540-aba9fdf176f1,F005,Planks of Promise,COMPLETED,AEPW,Philippines,Manila,PUBLISHED,"The Planks of Promise Project led by Plastic Flamingo (PLAF) provides a holistic solution for flexible and rigid plastic waste in Metro Manila. PLAF has established more than 100 collection bins across the city, with plastic waste aggregated for processing at their small factory. They have developed plans to recycle the captured waste into eco planks and post disaster emergency shelters. The project is located in Metro Manila (Philippines).  Their small sorting plant has been in operation since early June 2019, and they have developed the materials recipe using polyolefins with the University of Philippines capable of creating eco-planks from various plastics (HDPE, LDPE and PP). Plastic waste is sorted, shredded and flaked for extrusion into eco-planks and plastic pellets. The goal is to produce building materials for temporary shelters, outdoor furniture and decking. The project targets community engagement and education on the value of plastic waste and the importance of responsible plastic waste disposal. Project Objective The project aims to: Further develop plastic collection capabilities through the use of collection points and purchase of required materials Have a recycling facility up and running in 2021 to produce and sell recycled plastic eco-planks as well as to produce and sell post disaster shelter-kits, made from recycled plastic eco-planks Reach target goals of recycling 2,000 tons of plastic waste (HDPE,LDPE and PP) into eco-planks and shelters within the first 2 years of the project, and then 2,000 tons per year from the third year onwards. The forecast for this is as follows:  Year 1: 500 tons Year 2: 1,500 tons Year 3: 2,000 tons Approach Phase 1 Set up recycling facility Installation of three-phase electric power in the warehouse Installation of first extruder and other recycling equipment and materials Production of recycled plastic flakes Phase 2 Production and marketing eco planks Define the targeted visual and technical properties of the first sample of eco-planks Configure the extruder Testing technical properties of the eco-planks Production and sale of eco-planks Phase 3 Production and marketing of shelter kits Production of eco-planks and lumber for shelter kit Assembling prototype for testing Production and sale of shelter kits","Lead by The Plastic Flamingo (PLAF), this project provides a solution for flexible and rigid plastic waste to produce building materials for temporary shelters, outdoor furniture and decking.",,The Plastic Flamingo (PLAF),"[""14.59951200000000000"",""120.98421900000000000""]",ACTUAL,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
08b8f002-e364-478d-89ce-f95c4c928f43,I002,Plastic Recovery Insights Steering Model (PRISM),ACTIVE,AEPW,Singapore,Global,ARCHIVED,"The Plastic Recovery Insight and Steering Model (PRISM) has been developed to address the Data Gap. It is a platform that serves as a single source of consistent actionable data, allowing stakeholders to convene and unite various data sets to collaborate and address the challenge of plastic waste through data.  PRISM seeks to be an industry-leading repository of accurate and updated global plastic and plastic waste data at a sub-national level, that can enable the Alliance and other organisations worldwide to gain insights on the current plastic waste situation and derive viable interventions to manage plastic waste and reduce plastic leakage into the environment.  PRISM is envisioned as an open-source, science-based online platform,providing global plastic waste data (management and leakage) from various sources to enable organisations in their decision making on potential project investments. The project has gained high level of collaboration interests with global organisations such as IUCN, UN, WWF and others.  PRISM has been developed over the past year together with IBM Services in Singapore and is now available to members upon registration. Members are welcome to register by using the link: https://plasticinformation.org/auth/login  Project Objective The project aims to: Close the data gap  Attract investors by highlighting opportunities for impact Enrich the data repository with additional external sources and through collaborations with Universities, Researchers and Governmental Organisations and Nongovernmental Organisations Build models using data science for calculating leakage, building archetypes Approach Create a robust information platform to attract and catalyze investment, ensuring sound data driven basis for decision-making. Build a database to guide AEPW investment decisions in line with mission and strategy providing data to support portfolio management of themes and specific projects. Monitor progress against AEPW Outcomes, KPIs, and individual project roadmap. Link to the website: https://plasticinformation.org/auth/login Watch the Virtual Project Tour","The project aims to build a database to guide AEPW investment decisions, providing data to support portfolio management of themes and specific projects.",,IBM,"[""1.29115679484029580"",""103.78455680805310000""]",ESTIMATE,"Changi, Singapore",,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
cb62a07e-8853-4642-b8a1-9a0c5e306b3d,E023,Integrated Waste Management Facility,ACTIVE,AEPW,United States,"Omaha, Nebraska",PUBLISHED,"Firstar Fiber operates an existing 85 kt/yr. MRF serving the greater Omaha area, a small city in the Midwest of USA, with a population of approximately ~500k. The operations have historically offered only marginal profitability, squeezed between municipal collection contracts, high logistics costs for shipping recyclables to other locations and disposal costs to landfill/ incineration. Project Objective The project aims to: Increase the collection and conversion of film from curbside collection and post-agricultural use to 4kt/yr Demonstrate viable economics and higher recycling rates from co-location and integration of plastic lumber production and chemical recycling or other technologies at 13kt/yr Approach Phase 1 Install a pre-processing facility for plastic film waste from curb-side recyclable collection and the Hefty Energy Bag program. The facility comprises shredding, metal removal, cleaning, and conveying film including installation of the vacuum system for film waste Install a 1.3 kt/yr. plastic lumber extrusion facility  Launch commercial tenders for a pyrolysis plant to be owned and operated by Firstar Fiber to convert 7-14 kt/yr. of plastic waste to fuel/chemical feedstock and a 7-14 kt/yr. plant to convert mixed waste to construction materials Obtain funding for Phase 2 Phase 2 Expand flexibles and difficult-to-recycle plastic waste collection from a range of sources including post-consumer waste, commercial, and agricultural film waste Expand the pre-processing facility and install a compression mill producing free-flowing cubes to feed downstream operations Implement pyrolysis plant and/or plant to convert waste to construction products Progress an Education and Outreach program in collaboration with Keep Omaha Beautiful to enhance community awareness and engagement, track results of the program, and disseminate learnings and best practices in support of project replication.",The Firstar Fiber project aims to develop an integrated system to convert difficult-to-recycle plastic waste to its highest and best use by Firstar Fiber.,,Firstar Fiber,"[""41.21675415140068600"",""-96.07639701708615000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
9d99a855-0450-45c6-85c9-37709d41e211,J228,Revolutionizing the Reverse Vending Machine,ACTIVE,AEPW,Vietnam,Vietnam,SUBMITTED,"Targeting to divert up to 1.83KTA of food-grade PET bottles for recycling, Botol revolutionises the reverse vending machines sorts bottles with on-the-spot sorting and densification to significantly lower logistics cost. Through a collaboration with SuperIndo supermarkets, these machines will be installed in supermarkets and rewards customers with US.01/bottle discount coupons. Through this, the project will: Reduce unmanaged waste and capture value from waste by collecting and processing PET bottles into colour-sorted flakes for recycling Build new capacity designed for 3.672KTA Mobilise capital with co-funding Engage new partners to enable the ecosystem Create social benefit by jobs creation",Revolutionising the reverse vending machine with on-the-spot sorting and densification to significantly lower logistics cost,,BoTol,"[""14.43049816829994500"",""108.46620445457485000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
9a54f132-e2b3-4120-a85d-737963cdb65e,K029-GC,Hara Kal,ACTIVE,AEPW,India,Kohzikode; Kerala,PUBLISHED,"The project ( Hara Kal) provides a grant for additional collection of 1 KT of plastic waste from 6+ Villages in Kozhikode district of Kerala in the South of India. This project is a collaboration between Alliance to End Plastic Waste and rePurpose Global (rPG) Inc. that aims to deploy an end-to-end waste management supply chain. This early impact project addresses irregular low value plastic (LVP) collection, high marine plastic pollution and under-developed plastic waste management infrastructure across seven villages in Kozhikode district of Kerala. Kozhikode is one of the fastest growing districts of the state of Kerala. The district borders the Arabian Sea on the west and the Western Ghats - an eco-sensitive & biodiverse region - on the east.   70-80% of plastic packaging used in Kerala is comprised of low-value plastics that are currently either being burned or dumped in nature. This includes soft, flexible types of packaging such as candy wrappers and chips packets. Uncollected plastics obstruct the drainage systems, are burned illegally, or end up in streams and consequently, the ocean. Building on rePurpose's existing operations across the coastal village of Kerala, the project willenable the recovery of plastic waste and sending it for co-processing or recycling.   As a part of this project, Repurpose is collaborating with Green Worms Eco Solutions LLP (""Green Worms""), a waste management enterprise, to holistically engage with various parties across the plastic waste value chain such as households, rural waste collectors and waste processing facilities in 6+ villages in Kozhikode, for the collection and transportation of plastic waste.   The Project targets the collection and co-processing/recycling of 1 KT of various types of plastic waste within seven months.","This is an Early Impact Project (2 phases) which intends to recover 2.8 KT of flexible plastic waste across the coastal district of Kozhikode Villages, Kerala, India, for co-processing and recycling.",,Repurpose Global Inc,"[""11.26121087091904900"",""75.78197017012151000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
132f7801-bf60-4578-bfff-0861b96b955b,X002C,Scaling RESIN8 Solution for Hard to Recycle Plastics in Cape Town,ACTIVE,AEPW,South Africa,Cape Town,PUBLISHED,"This project will expand the existing Cape Town, South Africa, RESIN8 pilot plant into a commercial scale RESIN8 facility, capable of converting 7.3 KT of non-recyclable plastic waste per year, into 8.7 KT of RESIN8 per year. CRDC has received co-funding from another third-party thus catalysing Alliance's investment for the South African facility expansion. The commercial scale facility is expected to start up in mid-2023.   Strategic objectives: 1.       Demonstration of successful replication of scale up of CRDC's Cape Town pilot plant into a commercial scale operation by leveraging CRDC's learnings from prior Alliance projects. 2.       Providing an end market for recycling of plastic waste that would have otherwise ended up in landfill through the promotion of RESIN8.   Additional background: CRDC's mission is to create appreciating value from the world's plastic waste by converting it into RESIN8, an Eco-Aggregate that improves concrete. The Alliance is working with CRDC in the Americas and in Cape Town, to provide a solution for difficult-to-recycle plastics by helping CRDC to: a.     Expand their RESIN8 pilot plant in Costa Rica to a commercial scale operation. b.     Build a new RESIN8 facility in York, PA (USA). c. Replicating the TBTB program in another geography after success in the Americas. c.    With support from the Alliance,  CRDC started a pilot of The Bag That Builds (TBTB) program in Cape Town, South Africa, in late-2022. TBTB is a way to engage communities and ramp up new plastic waste feedstock sources in anticipation of their soon to be expanded RESIN8 facility. d.     TBTB is designed to simplify the collection of plastic waste so that any type of plastic waste (Resins 1-7) can be put into a single recycling bag, eliminating the need to separate and segregate different types of plastic. e.     Plastic collected via TBTB will be sorted to remove high value plastics which will be sold, and the remaining lower value plastics will be converted into RESIN8.","This project converts difficult-to-recycle plastic waste into RESIN8, an Eco-Aggregate used in concrete. Together with CRDC, it aims to expand their current RESIN8 pilot plant in Cape Town.",,CRDC (Center for Regenerative Design & Collaboration),"[""-33.92584123737663000"",""18.41430911437067400""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
5c95e4c0-3a97-4c28-a591-012bcc5f889d,J219GC,Buat Bumi,ACTIVE,AEPW,Indonesia,Tangerang,PUBLISHED,"Tridi Oasis is a female-led Indonesian recycling company aiming to turn problems in waste management into opportunities by recycling local plastic waste into usable raw materials. With Indonesia being the second largest contributor of ocean plastics in the world, generating more than 3.2m tons of mismanaged plastic waste annually and producing 1.29m tons of marine debris, Tridi Oasis has risen to the occasion with its production of recycled PET flakes to advance the circular economy and help reduce plastic wastage. With its current business model having taken off and stabilised, Tridi Oasis aims to be a pioneer in recycling flexible plastics and MLPs while simultaneously creating a bigger environmental impact. Project Objectives Produce and test 1,000 pieces of recycled plastic pallets in 10 different companies Collect 55 tons per month of MLP plastics , and 250 tons per month of PET plastics for recycling through the expansion of collection channels Increase the number of beneficiaries through job creation, and increase in collection channels Approach Set up a team with expertise to focus on MLP collection and recycling in Tangerang Complete R&D and feasibility study, covering finalisation of product design, production design, environmental impact analysis, market study and assessment, and product testing and certification Conduct capacity training for informal waste collection and setup waste collection network with 'warungs' (small shops) and minimarket to start a collection of MLPs Pallet production and product trials to gather feedback and evaluation for product design",Expand collection of waste PET through strategic partnership to include flexible plastics/ multi-layered plastics (MLP),,PT Tridi Oasis Group,"[""-6.27663569684064450"",""106.60335663966400000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
749c1da9-adc2-405e-8b5e-77e983f7fad5,K102-GC,Milkar Kare Sambhav,ACTIVE,AEPW,India,Multiple Cities,PUBLISHED,"Circular Sustainability Solutions collaborates with enterprises and enables them to close their material loops by designing and implementing transformative Extended Producer Responsibility (EPR) programmes. In September 2019, an industry coalition (PACE) announced the setup of a new plastic management venture in partnership with Karo Sambhav (brand name). The project aims to collect/recycle 1.3 KT of plastic within a period of 12 months after enhancement of 4 existing collection centres and supply chain. Project Objectives Collection of 1.3 KT plastic waste in addition to e-waste - to be directed away from landfills/leakages and recycled/co processed in the period of 9 months post set up of collection centres Engaging informal sector workers through capacity building, formalization and job creation - estimated 32 direct jobs created via this project Ensuring responsible recycling by channelizing sorted waste to authorised recyclers and processors Conducting outreach and awareness activities with estimated 75,000-200,000 residents, waste pickers, aggregators, bulk consumers, RWAs etc Approach Collection of Plastic Waste Expansion of existing collection centres Installation of machinery (sorting and baling) based on the needs and volume of incoming waste Setting up of systems for sorting and processing of plastic waste Designing and operationalizing decentralised collection chains with waste collectors, repairing shop, rag pickers, aggregators, bulk consumers, etc. Formalising of informal sector workers and integrating them into collection chains Moving collected plastic waste to authorised recyclers/processors Awareness and Capacity Building of Stakeholders Undertaking training and capacity building activities for various collection partners Upskilling of the centre workers to recognise and differentiate between different grades and types of plastic Conducting awareness activities such as consumer workshops, school awareness programmes, upskilling for aggregators, workshops for ULBs etc.",Incremental collection by expanding current e-waste collection channels to include plastic waste and its waste management. Also involved in waste diversion from the landfill and plastic waste management and disposal.,,Circular Sustainability Solutions Pte Ltd,"[""29.00460575314819000"",""77.12877409128029000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
e4306d89-d40e-456f-b792-be601e7c762d,X002D,Closing the Gap with Reclaimers,COMPLETED,AEPW,South Africa,Johannesburg; Mayflower,PUBLISHED,"The project will be implemented in Mayflower, a rural village in Mpumalanga Province outside of Johannesburg as well as in Johannesburg city itself. The lack of recycling facilities within Mayflower and the absence of cost-effective transportation options to bring the collected waste to neighbouring cities have resulted in large scale improper disposal of waste (e.g. via open burning, dumping). This project intends to improve the situation by addressing these specific challenges. Project Objective The project aims to: Improve the plastic waste collection and sorting rates in Mayflower and Johannesburg; Support informal waste reclaimers in a rural setting by improving livelihoods of these individuals; Replicate and scale-up project to other nearby communities/ villages. Approach The 9-month pilot project will include: Mobilisation of informal reclaimers (80-100pax) in both Mayflower and Johannesburg to collect plastic waste; Establishment of a transportation network of plastic waste and table waste from Mayflower to Johannesburg; and Rental of space in Johannesburg to be used for sorting and aggregation of plastic waste before sale.","The project aims to improve the collection, sorting and recycling rates in Mayflower and Johannesburg with the help of ARO, a non-profit organisation based in Johannesburg.",,African Reclaimers Organisation (ARO),"[""-26.16133027723010300"",""30.79647144423092800""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
43c3dcca-f091-4395-9476-35be6b53414a,X002CG,Bringing The Bag That Builds Program to South Africa,ACTIVE,AEPW,South Africa,Cape Town,PUBLISHED,"CRDC Global is an existing project partner with funding provided for two RESIN8 facilities in the Americas: a pilot plant expansion in Costa Rica and a new plant in York, PA (USA). CRDC takes difficult to recycle plastics and converts it into an eco-aggregate, called RESIN8, used in concrete which is then used to build homes and other buildings in surrounding communities.  CRDC developed The Bag That Builds (TBTB) program as a way to engage communities and enable more avenues to collect feedstock for their RESIN8 facilities. TBTB is designed to simplify the collection of plastic waste and it is designed so that any type of plastic waste (Resins 1-7) can be put into a single recycling bag, eliminating the need to separate and segregate different types of plastic. Plastic collected via TBTB will be sorted to remove high value plastics which will be sold, and the remaining lower value plastics will be converted into RESIN8. This early impact project focuses on bringing TBTB to Cape Town, South Africa, where there is currently a RESIN8 pilot facility. CRDC plans to roll out TBTB to new collection points throughout the city including housing developments, schools, waste reclaimers, Rugby World Cups Sevens events, beach and river clean-ups, and mixed-use development areas. In parallel, CRDC is in process of expanding this pilot facility to a full-scale commercial operation. Plastics collected via TBTB in Cape Town will be taken to sorting locations where valuable plastics will be sorted for resale. The low value plastics will be sent to CRDC's Cape Town pilot plant to be processed into RESIN8 and any surplus low value plastic will be stored and eventually processed into RESIN8 once the full-scale plant is operational, targeted for Q2-2023. AEPW has approved grant funding of US,000 to cover both CAPEX and OPEX costs related to the bringing TBTB to South Africa. The project kicked off in August 2022 and has been working hard to start delivering impact already in 2022. The project is expected to complete by end of 2023, with an expected total impact of 680 tons.","This project brings CRDC Global's The Bag That Builds (TBTB) program to Cape Town, South Africa. It engages communities, simplifies the collection and increases recycling of plastic waste.",,CRDC Global,"[""-33.92584123737663000"",""18.41430911437067400""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
65917a58-b4e7-45cd-b1a9-eb720befff9c,K105,Flex Plastic Waste Recycling in Kenya,ACTIVE,AEPW,Kenya,Nairobi,PUBLISHED,"The Project consists of scaling up the project partner's current flexible recycling operations by constructing a new flexible plastic processing plant, fed by new Buy Back Centers set up in Kenya, and equipped with innovative machines (such as washing line, pelletizer, and a wastewater treatment facility). The project targets impact of over 20 KTA of plastic collected at maturity and over 14 KTA of plastic recycled at maturity.",Taka Taka Solutions: flexible plastic processing,,Taka Taka Solutions,"[""-1.23444804822618330"",""36.75494033740755000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
d2e6804e-f452-4f0b-8ee2-c3f47bd4e74f,X002,South Africa Flagship Project,ACTIVE,AEPW,South Africa,Johannesburg; Durban; Cape Town,PUBLISHED,"Globally, South Africa is ranked 11th in terms of plastic waste leakage and plastic consumption is expected to increase by ~3% each year. Despite a significant collection rate, relying heavily on the informal sector, 40% of packaging waste is mismanaged and only 14% is effectively recycled.   However, there is willingness within the country to address this situation, as seen by the move from a voluntary to a mandatory EPR system as well as the development of strategic waste management plans at municipal level. Project Objective   The South Africa Flagship will address four main Circularity Gaps across two priority archetypes: Urban formal and informal settlements in a district of Johannesburg, and  Urban coastal communities, in Amanzimtoti, south of Durban and Cape Town. The gaps to be addressed are: Data, Alignment (social), Quality and Quantity.   Approach  In Johannesburg, efforts will be taken to improve the collection and sorting of plastics using a data-led approach to interventions. GreenCape will conduct a detailed feasibility study over a 9-month period which will include a baseline assessment, brokering of partnerships between key stakeholders (e.g. Local authorities and informal waste sector), community engagement with the long-term goal of developing end markets and a proposal to improve waste management infrastructure.   In parallel, we will also support the well-organised reclaimer community, led by the African Reclaimers Organisation (""ARO""), to collect plastics waste from 2 locations: Mayflower (rural village next to Johannesburg) and the city of Johannesburg. The collected waste will be aggregated and sorted in a new pilot sorting facility in Johannesburg for onward sale to local recyclers such as ExtruPET. The goal is to generate early impact, build trust with key players and develop our market understanding.   In the coastal cities of Durban and Cape Town, boosting plastic waste collection will be key. We will work with the South Africa Healthcare Foundation to scale up the existing Inkwazi Isu program. This comprises sorting infrastructure upgrades, clean-ups, as well as education and awareness campaigns. Phase 2 will then focus on the development of suitable solutions and end-markets for aggregated plastic waste from our interventions in South Africa. In the longer term, once proven successful, the solutions developed could be replicated across South Africa and regionally via the global Plastics Pact network, which is in turn supported by Alliance Strategic Ally, UK-based charity WRAP. Related Projects Inkwazi Isu Building an inclusive system to tackle plastic waste' Bringing The Bag That Builds Program to S. Africa Closing the Gap with Reclaimers","The Flagship focuses on developing collection and sorting models in inland and coastal cities in South Africa, later including the development of downstream options and end markets.",,"GreenCape, South Africa Healthcare Foundation, ARO and CRDC","[""-30.02830242262380600"",""30.89439708445748800""]",ESTIMATE,Duplicate,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
49700850-0ca9-468b-aadc-8ee7bf3350eb,H010,EPS Recycling en Bretagne,ACTIVE,AEPW,France,Brittany,SUBMITTED,"Expanded polystyrene (EPS) exhibits a notably low density owing to its predominantly air-based composition. This characteristic imparts significant attributes such as thermal insulation and resilience against impact and shock. However, this inherent low density poses challenges to EPS recycling, primarily due to logistical complexities rather than technical constraints. A proposed solution involves compacting EPS into blocks to optimise transport efficiency and streamline recycling processes, and preferably mounted on a truck.
Implementation of such collection trucks is contingent upon operating within a geographically feasible area conducive to conducting collection rounds within specified timeframes. Consequently, a feasibility study primarily focuses on the Brittany region. This phase entails the mapping of EPS end-users across various sectors including aquaculture, fish transportation and processing, food packaging, and construction. Waste management and recycling solutions are also part of the mapping.
To achieve the objective, the project is divided into three phases:
#1: Study of the PSE waste deposit in Brittany
#2: Collection/ compaction
Realize a state of the art compaction solution and its adaptation to a truck. Validation of partnerships on the collection, logistics and operation of a press. There are already collection solutions that require the immobilization of an area to store EPS waste. The establishment of a storage area is not always feasible. The project provides a complementary solution for all these sites limited by space or those with lower EPS consumption.
#3: Recycling
Different recycling solutions will be evaluated depending on whether or not a return to food contact is needed. Chemical recycling solutions will be evaluated for return to food contact. An analysis of the contaminants present in the collected streams will then be necessary.
The implementation of a truck will be enabled mainly by identifying a collection point that does not yet have recycling solutions. This may include sites with a limited storage capacity that does not allow collection with existing solutions (e.g. collection by trucks for quantities > 20 m³).
This type of mobile compaction and collection system makes the project in the region unique.
The project will reduce the incineration and landfilling of EPS by increasing the recycling rate. This increase will be made possible by the capture of dispersed EPS streams. The project will also reduce marine pollution by EPS.","The project aims to map the miscellaneous EPS waste generators from small businesses and industry in Brittany, France then setup an optimized logistic scheme to collect the EPS waste volumes and bring them to local recyclers.",,,"[""48.08188477900476000"",""-1.76635058455637340""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
2bde112c-9e62-458d-97de-352c3906b509,K013,MGA Plastic Collection & Recycling Program,ACTIVE,AEPW,Kenya,Nairobi,PUBLISHED,"MGA is a private enterprise based in Nairobi, Kenya with a vision to be the leader in the Global South in supplying brand owners and industrial buyers with traceable high quality recycled plastics, positioning social and environmental impact at the core of a financially, sustainable, and scalable business model. By 2030, MGA aims to collect and convert 100 kt/year of all plastic types, realizing  million in annual revenue through sale of recyclates and revenue via EPR schemes. The proposed project, which will run for approximately 36 months but have long lasting effects on MGA collection and processing capabilities, will focus on supporting the development and expansion of the MGA Collection Network; developing food grade conversation capacity for HDPE/PP and PET; and building a strategy and capacity to address hard to recycle materials.  Project Objective The objective of this project is to: 1. Develop and expand the MGA Collection Network by 37.2 KT per year by 2026 through the scale-up of the MGA consumer-facing collection model and increased collection of PET and flexible materials through the MGA informal sector collection models 2. Develop food grade conversion capacity for HDPE/PP and PET leading to a total increase in conversion capacity of 30.1 KT per year by 2026  3. Build a plastic laboratory in Nairobi and target collection of all plastics while developing a strategic market review towards recycling/recovery of hard to recycle materials   Approach Phase 1 Support the development and expansion of the MGA Collection Network, including: - Integrating computer vision/machine learning technologies into MGA operations to improve consumer experience (a new supplier category) and convert transactions into tangible data;  - Developing a retail/brand owner engagement model to increase the value of MGA Green Points and allow consumers to purchase more valuable and desired goods;  - Scaling the MGA Collection Network by integrating 1,940 Approved Aggregation Partners (AAPs) into MGAs formal value chain.   Phase 2 Develop food grade conversion capacity, including: - Upgrading the existing MGA facility (EA Hub) to allow for food grade processing of rHDPE/PP, and rPET;   - Increasing installed capacity at the EA hub from 250 MT to 1200-1500 MT per month.  Phase 3 Build a strategy and internal capacity to derive value from hard to recycle materials, including: - Building a state-of-the-art plastics laboratory in Nairobi, allowing MGA to become a leader in plastics material science in Africa; - Developing a strategic framework outlining MGA's approach to derive value from hard to recycle materials and producing profitable product lines across Africa. ",The Alliance is supporting MGA with loans to scale collection activities in Kenya as well as for the purchase of processing equipment for rigid plastic waste.,,Mr Green Africa,"[""-1.32805657576999110"",""36.86561690892827000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
49026511-a260-4d34-a9dc-69637568c44b,J020,Cidades+,ACTIVE,AEPW,Brazil,Multiple Cities,PUBLISHED,"This project leverages an established waste aggregation and recycling model successfully demonstrated by Instituto Recicleiros in Ceará (northeast Brazil). Recicleiros Cidades works with municipalities, bringing together city governments, waste pickers, companies and citizens in a circular value chain. By 2023, the project targets activity in 60 cities across 26 Brazilian states, bringing innovation and technology, and transforming lives. The cities are provided with waste collection and basic MRF infrastructure and a commitment to improving waste management, increasing recycling rates and reducing leakage to the environment.",This project leverages an established waste aggregation and recycling model successfully demonstrated by Instituto Recicleiros in Ceará (northeast Brazil).,,Instituto Recicleiros,"[""-23.57531129440827700"",""-46.57602279752896000""]",ESTIMATE,São Paulo,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
8e73c6ab-358d-4ddf-b92a-17d335c8bfcc,J100-GC,Let's Transform,ACTIVE,AEPW,India,Delhi; Ghaziaba; Pandurna; Cochin ; Coimbatore,PUBLISHED,"Saahas Zero Waste (SZW) is a social enterprise that provides end to end waste management services. SZW is working to bring about environmental and social change based on the principles of circular economy and global commitment to Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). The starting point for this early impact project is a social inclusion programme for the informal sector working with waste. This includes waste aggregators and scrap dealers. Collectively, this community and its value chain manages more than 90% of the country's waste. One of the key attributes of this project is to demonstrate an approach where micro-entrepreneurs who work within the informal sector now have access to financial as well as managerial support so that they can have a formalized healthy business. In this project, we will work with 4 micro-entrepreneurs in the National Capital Region (Delhi-NCR), Bangalore (in Karnataka), Pandhurna (in Madhya Pradesh) and Cochin (in Kerala) to collect and process mostly low value plastic waste.",Diversion of mostly low value plastic waste from the environment for co-processing in cement kilns/ recycling and social inclusion of informal sector entrepreneurs.,,Saahas Waste Management Pte Ltd,"[""28.68585911313480700"",""77.22086722742753000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
db0ceaff-6389-4fbf-801e-f427e80b51ca,O005,The Alliance Prize,COMPLETED,AEPW,United States,Global,PUBLISHED,"Flexible plastics are one of the most difficult to recycle waste streams and the circularity of flexibles is yet to be achieved. This issue can be attributed to a combination of design gaps for recyclability, lack of high-quality recyclates derived from flexibles and lack of infrastructure (collection, sorting and processing) that is fit-for-purpose for this stream. Therefore, The Alliance Prize is being undertaken with Carrot, a world leader in developing and implementing programmes to identify novel solutions that are Impactful, Scalable, Feasible, and Innovative that will extract a high value of high-quality, fit-for-purpose recyclates from flexible films found in household waste. The winning solution will be granted US million dollars for game-changing solutions to advance a circular economy for flexibles and the applications will be assessed through a comprehensive panel of judges from the plastics value chain - raw material producers, plastic product manufacturers, brand owners and civil societies both from the Alliance's member companies and other organisations. The judges were selected based on their expertise on plastics value chain knowledge and experience as well as regional representation to ensure diverse aspects are considered. The program is open for registrations until 26th July 2022 with submissions due by 23rd August 2022, after which the applications will go through evaluation and selection for final pitch event on 10th January 2023. https://www.circularsolutions.theallianceprize.org/","The Alliance Prize is a competition to identify and fund novel, circular solutions for flexible plastic waste.",,Carrot,"[""40.70729844879837000"",""-74.01126578110174000""]",ESTIMATE,New York Stock Exchange,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
98fd49ae-56df-419a-908b-8543c167c93d,M005,Hospital Waste Study,COMPLETED,AEPW,United Kingdom,United Kingdom,PUBLISHED,"In collaboration with the United Kingdom's National Health Service (NHS) and executed by PA Consulting, this CEO Seed Fund project will analyse hospital waste and identify opportunities to reduce plastic waste generated by the provision of medical services in UK hospitals, most of which is currently incinerated. Findings from the study are expected to comprise a combination of stronger nationwide purchasing and waste management practices and deployment of new technologies. The results will be published in a playbook for adoption in other UK hospitals and available to all regions and future Alliance city projects.","Fund project will analyse hospital waste and identify opportunities to reduce plastic waste generated by the provision of medical services in UK hospitals, most of which is currently incinerated.",,PA Consulting,"[""51.50969240364837000"",""-0.12276943434411292""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
454a04e6-a284-4ac0-835e-9bca78127041,X002B,Building an Inclusive System to Tackle Plastic Waste,ACTIVE,AEPW,South Africa,Johannesburg (Greater Alexandra area),PUBLISHED,"The City of Johannesburg recognizes the importance of addressing the plastic waste issue and has rolled out an integrated waste management plan spanning infrastructure, logistics planning, and initiatives for improving separation at source. However, despite efforts made, more can be done to further enhance the plastic circularity in this megacity. Project Objective The main objectives of this project are to address wastage of plastic resources in the rapidly developing north western region of Johannesburg, by: Increasing collection and sorting of plastics from middle to high income residential areas, by supporting informal waste pickers and enhancing buyback centres. Reducing direct plastic leakage into the environment in low-income areas, through a model of alternative service delivery. Incentivising and mobilising demand for recycled plastics through engaging with the private and public sector. Increasing citizen and business engagement in the responsible use of plastics through awareness and behaviour change campaigns. Approach The Project will bring together an experienced group of experts such as academics and environmental consultants to work with local stakeholders including the City of Johannesburg and the African Reclaimers Organisation (ARO) among others, to create a plastic circular economy. In the feasibility phase, GreenCape will conduct extensive research (e.g. surveys, waste characterisation studies) to determine the baseline conditions and understanding of local perceptions of plastic waste disposal, collection, and management. Armed with the insights from the feasibility study, GreenCape will then design and propose a range of interventions to improve collection and sorting of plastics from both the mid-high income residents as well as informal settlements in the greater Alexandra area. The proposal will include recommendations to create systems to minimise direct leakage of plastics into the environment and stimulate demand for recycled plastics through business and citizen engagement.",AEPW has partnered with GreenCape Sector Development Agency to conduct a feasibility study to better characterize plastic waste and consumer profiles in Johannesburg.,,GreenCape Sector Development Agency,"[""-26.05630665611002800"",""28.09705909278451200""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
a46e9554-d516-4172-afe9-03e0b1e58448,X002A,Inkwazi Isu Project,ACTIVE,AEPW,South Africa,Durban,PUBLISHED,"Following a severe flood in KwaZulu Natal in 2019, a team led by the SAHF and supported by Sasol conducted a baseline study of the area to define the waste problem and subsequently designed interventions to address plastic pollution in the area of the upper south coast, mainly the Amazimtoti and Zimnokodweni catchment areas. AEPW is supporting the scaled up implementation of the proposed interventions over a 4-year period. This includes: rivers and beach cleanups, upgrading of collection and sorting infrastructure, as well as community education. Project Objective SAHF will be leading the project as part of AEPWs South Africa Flagship programme, in locations that are characterised as urban and coastal, within Durban, to boost collection and enhance downstream processing opportunities: Increase opportunities for plastic waste to be collected and diverted from landfill and the environment by expanding the impact of the Project. Demonstrate how bringing together smaller plastic waste actions into a larger, organised operation can bring greater scale and impact for a region.   Collect and collate a reliable plastic feedstock supporting the development of recycling and processing activities, hence the enhanced availability of recyclates in the region.   Scale up and replicate the project in coastal areas of South Africa.  Approach Upgrade 10 Durban Solid Waste Garden Sites into recycling hubs - increasing the capacity to sort plastic waste collected at the sites to be sent to recycling or alternative processing methods.  Develop and deliver a marketing and communication strategy for the community, making them aware of the facilities and opportunities to recycle available to them.  Create and deliver educational resource materials, educating 105 schools.   Undertake a recurring schedule of clean-up campaigns along rivers and beaches, including the cleanup of the identified and mapped waste hotspots.  Identify, assess, and develop a detailed proposal for downstream processing options and scale up / replication opportunities. ","AEPW has partnered with non-profit organization, the South Africa Healthcare Foundation to enhance plastic waste collection and sorting systems in the urban-coastal area of Durban.",,South Africa Healthcare Foundation,"[""-30.01855395996021000"",""30.89507237975659000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
be50b8c4-6e6a-4bf8-b7d2-c018d0310d07,J100-GC,Let's Transform,ACTIVE,AEPW,India,Delhi; Ghaziaba; Pandurna; Cochin ; Coimbatore,PUBLISHED,"Saahas Zero Waste (SZW) is a social enterprise that provides end to end waste management services. SZW is working to bring about environmental and social change based on the principles of circular economy and global commitment to Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). The starting point for this early impact project is a social inclusion programme for the informal sector working with waste. This includes waste aggregators and scrap dealers. Collectively, this community and its value chain manages more than 90% of the country's waste. One of the key attributes of this project is to demonstrate an approach where micro-entrepreneurs who work within the informal sector now have access to financial as well as managerial support so that they can have a formalized healthy business. In this project, we will work with 4 micro-entrepreneurs in the National Capital Region (Delhi-NCR), Bangalore (in Karnataka), Pandhurna (in Madhya Pradesh) and Cochin (in Kerala) to collect and process mostly low value plastic waste.",Diversion of mostly low value plastic waste from the environment for co-processing in cement kilns/ recycling and social inclusion of informal sector entrepreneurs.,,Saahas Waste Management Pte Ltd,"[""21.59213453845466000"",""78.53043301310329000""]",ESTIMATE,"Bangalore, Delhi and Pandhurna",,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
234a70a9-f7e2-4a67-8b31-897997190605,,Tridi Oasis-Alba PET JV,ACTIVE,AEPW,Indonesia,"Kendal, Central Java",DRAFT,"Background Tridi Oasis is a female-led homegrown Indonesian recycling company. They operate an existing 12 kta PET fibre plant in Tangerang, Java and are already working with the Alliance on an Early Impact project for the collection and recycling of multi-layer plastic waste that is progressing well.  Tridi Oasis will be forming a joint venture named PT Alba Tridi Plastics Recycling with waste management company Alba Asia Plastics Recycling Limited. Tridi Oasis' CEO has founded PT Dhara Daya Sustainea, which will be the minority shareholder in the JV contributing the existing operations of Tridi Oasis, while Alba will be the majority shareholder. The new venture will leverage strengths from both partners, with PT Dhara Daya Sustainea contributing a strong local network for feedstock sourcing, as well as community and government engagement, while Alba brings expertise in waste management and recycling operations, leveraging Alba's global technical know-how, operational excellence, and internationally reputable brand.  Project Objectives The Project consists of building a PET recycling plant of 34 kta output capacity (48 kta max throughput capacity) to produce food grade recycled PET (rPET) pellets and flakes in Kendal Industrial Park, Central Java, Indonesia. The bottle-to-bottle recycling plant will provide high quality rPET food grade PCR for the local and global markets.   The plant will provide jobs and steady incomes for local Indonesians in the plastic waste value chain including informal waste pickers, junkshop owners, and other waste aggregators. While PET collection and recycling are increasing in Indonesia, there remains continued leakage and value loss of unmanaged waste plastic PET.  Project Approach AEPW is providing up to .6 M shareholder loan to minority shareholder PT Dhara Daya Sustainea to support the 48 kta food grade rPET project. Alba Asia is the majority shareholder partner and Asian Development Bank is the senior lender providing up to .2M blue loan to the project.",Tridi Oasis-Alba PET JV aims to build a greenfield plant in Central Java to facilitate recycling of post consumer PET as part of efforts to encourage plastic and closed-loop recycling in light of regulatory shifts in acceptance of rPET for food contact.,,,"[""-6.83429358284353900"",""110.25987827698256000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
550b0c9c-5029-48a0-aad8-722f5deb8eff,J040-GC,Circular Action BV (BVRio),ACTIVE,AEPW,Brazil,Rio de Janerio,PUBLISHED,"The CAP model is a customized service based on engaging all parties in the waste supply chain and providing incentives to increase collection, sorting, and recycling of waste materials. The system is managed using supply chain traceability and monitoring tools (via KOLEKT, a mobile app and reporting platform) specifically developed for the programme to register all parties participating in waste management supply chains to enable traceability of waste along the supply chain. Project Objectives The project is focused on increasing plastic recovery efforts in connection with two cooperatives in Duque de Caxias, located in the state of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. Coopama, Rio de Janeiro - increase truck fleet to enable more residential and commercial collection of plastic waste with target impact of 1.27KT of plastic waste recycled Enables cooperative to expand their recyclables pickup service and contract steady collection at large apartment complexes, shopping malls, hospitals, and other commercial businesses Register all volumes of non-recyclable plastics and develop business case for pyrolysis Mobile app monitoring of waste collections and sales Cooper Ecológica, Rio de Janeiro - incentivize informal waste sector to collect more types of plastic waste with target impact of 560T of plastic waste (HDPE/LDPE) recycled Kickstart demand and therefore collection of HDPE and LDPE in Rio de Janeiro Kickstart use of the KOLEKT mobile app for trading and monitoring of waste streams Register all volumes of non-recyclable plastics and develop a business case for pyrolysis Approach Coopama, Rio de Janeiro Project will request condominiums and businesses to sort their plastic waste, which will then be posted online via BVRio's KOLEKT waste trading app to trigger pickup by the cooperative. Waste will be brought back to the cooperative for sorting; recyclables will be sold to recyclers - sales of recyclables and rejects will be monitored on KOLEKT Proceeds of sales will be kept, in its entirety, by the cooperative of waste pickers Cooper Ecológica, Rio de Janeiro Engage and incentivize independent waste pickers not employed by the cooperative to collect and deliver HDPE and LDPE plastics to a designated aggregate point or directly to the cooperative facility Cooper Ecológica will do all purchase transactions with independent waste pickers using the KOLEKT app, inclusive of paying them and registering all purchases in real time HDPE/LDPE will be sold to local recyclers, in which net proceeds of sales will be kept by the cooperative of waste pickers after deducting the payments made to individual waste collectors.","Circular Action BV operates a Circular Action Programme (CAP) consisting of 3 phases of preparation, inception, operation and administration of CAP in Brazil.",,Circular Action BV,"[""-22.78682637695258600"",""-43.31509283146680000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
a39ab3cc-77e1-4e6d-8c0a-6eac5f8aa08b,J220-GC,Clean Fuel Malaysia,ACTIVE,AEPW,Malaysia,Klang,PUBLISHED,"ResourceCo Asia (M) Sdn Bhd (RAM) is a local manufacturer of Process Engineered Fuel (PEF) in Malaysia, with a PEF plant in Ipoh, Perak, and a waste collection radius covering the entire Peninsula. Through this project, RAM looks to remove 4,200 tonnes of aged, weathered dumpsite of legacy plastic rejects from abandoned recycling activities. The first site in Bandar Amada Putra, Klang, Selangor, is estimated to contain approximately 1,200 tons of non-recyclable plastic anonymously dumped and scattered in the open environment. Project Objectives The project aims to remove approximately 4,200 tonnes of legacy plastic rejects from abandoned recycling dumpsites. Collection and co-processing of 1,200 tonnes of non-recyclable plastic waste within first 3 months  Collection and co-processing of another 3,000 tonnes of non-recyclable plastic waste within the next 5 months, bringing total amount to 4,200t by end 2022 Approach Engagement and interaction with local stakeholders (DOE, NSWD, Majilis, NGOS, etc) Site inspection, material sampling, applicability study, process proposal Mobilization of equipment (excavator, truck, loader), crew and supervisor Sorting, loading and transportation from sites to Ipoh RDF plant Processing of incoming waste into PEF by RAM and its co-processing Records of mass balance and material repurposing rate","This project works with local municipalities to remove aged, weathered legacy plastic rejects from abandoned recycling activities in various sites.",,Resourceco Asia (M) Sdn Bhd,"[""2.98205897522998460"",""101.34494537426747000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
380cc33f-58d6-4363-bda9-efbfe4448541,8,Plastic Data Challenge - baseline data in Visakhapatnam,COMPLETED,AEPW,India,Visakhapatnam,ARCHIVED,"As part of the Project, the Feasibility Study will be conducted in Visakhapatnam, a metropolitan coastal city in Andhra Pradesh, India. Deliverables provided under the Feasibility Study will be submitted to AEPW in Microsoft Excel format. Datasets will be restructured in a format (a) to perform plastic pollution hot spotting, and (b) in collaboration with The Circulative Initiative and AEPW such that it is suitable for ingestion into PRISM or that which can be utilized for further data modelling purposes. ",The aim of the Project is to provide a rationale for a methodological and sampling approach that will meaningfully improve the available data for the chosen geography and prioritize areas where direct data collection can be conducted on the ground.,,TCI,"[""17.69870501304574600"",""83.23785369450549000""]",ESTIMATE,Duplicate,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
2eb8e06a-e23e-41ca-8ece-c2098282e7fc,X001,Vietnam Flagship Programme,ACTIVE,AEPW,Vietnam,"Hanoi; Ho Chi Minh City, Vung Tau",PUBLISHED,"The Vietnam Flagship Programme aims to develop and demonstrate a large scale, integrated waste management model that can attract catalytic capital for replication and will have a tangible impact towards resolution of the plastic waste issue in Vietnam. According to a recent study by National Plastic Action Partnership (""NPAP"") Vietnam, a business-as-usual scenario will result in mismanaged plastic waste doubling by 2030 to approximately 3 million tonnes per annum. Currently, 51% of plastic waste is mismanaged or leaked into the environment while 38% is incinerated or goes to landfill and only a mere 11% is recycled (either formally or informally). Project Objective: The objective of the Programme is to implement a multi-city initiative to increase collection and sorting of plastic waste as well as aggregation and development of end markets for recyclates. The programme, if successful, would improve the waste management situation for at least 15-20% of the total population in Vietnam via projects that will be implemented in major cities such as Hanoi, Ho Chi Minh City (HCMC) and Vung Tau.   Approach: In order to better understand the current waste management situation in Vietnam, a feasibility study (""FS"") will be conducted over a 9-month period, with targeted completion by Q1 2023 (Project X001A). The FS will be led by SNV, the appointed Project Management Office (""PMO""), and will serve to provide insights to key components such as waste baseline assessment, end market and informal waste collectors (IWCs) assessment. At the same time, AEPW will also leverage work done from another on-going feasibility study in Vung Tau. This is conducted by EnviroSC (and funded by Cities Development Initiative for Asia ""CDIA"") - X001B. At the end of this FS (estimated end '22), there will be opportunity for AEPW to assess and participate in recommended projects for waste management improvements in Vung Tau. In parallel, AEPW will also source and fund smaller scale early impact projects (in selected cities- Hanoi, HCMC, Vung Tau) to gain access to existing incumbents in the Vietnam plastic waste circular economy and derive hands-on learning of the local business environment. These learnings will be beneficial in ensuring the longer term success of the overall Vietnam flagship programme.  Related Projects X001E- Plastic Cycle",Vietnam has an increasing plastic consumption but limited waste management infrastructure. The government of Vietnam is committed to improve the situation with recent policy interventions.,,"SNV, EnviroSC etc.","[""21.03606409190374000"",""105.81886736103445000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
