recommended projects for waste management improvements in Vung Tau. In parallel, AEPW will also source and fund smaller scale early impact projects (in selected cities- Hanoi, HCMC, Vung Tau) to gain access to existing incumbents in the Vietnam plastic waste circular economy and derive hands-on learning of the local business environment. These learnings will be beneficial in ensuring the longer term success of the overall Vietnam flagship programme.  Related Projects X001E- Plastic Cycle",Vietnam has an increasing plastic consumption but limited waste management infrastructure. The government of Vietnam is committed to improve the situation with recent policy interventions.,,"SNV, EnviroSC etc.","[""10.41109460392226000"",""107.14261464015338000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
a6f55244-713f-4440-899e-6e93ef2e4803,M035,Megloo Re-use Japan,COMPLETED,AEPW,Japan,Tokyo,PUBLISHED,"Background Kaman were one of the top 11 companies in the Plug and Play Tokyo 2022 cohort. The initial business model for their re-use system was developed in the city of Kamakura in 2021, including an app system and polypropylene containers. The project targets the further development of the business model by enabling expansion of Kaman's reusable lunch box container sharing service. Project Objectives The project targets the expansion of the Megloo Re-Use concept in Japan with grant funding of  from the Alliance. The funding will enable Kaman to reduce single-use plastic consumption and plastic waste via (a) expansion of its existing reusable 'lunchbox' container system, (b) upgrading the functions and features of its existing mobile application on the instant communication app Line, and (c) conducting 'field pilots' at various locations. This will result in an estimated avoided use of virgin plastics of 50 tons by 2025, with corresponding savings in CO 2 . Approach The project consists of the development and expansion of existing business model based on findings obtained through conducting field pilots in in three archetypal locations: a small town a larger city, such as Yokohama or Shibuya with a delivery service provider, if possible large-scale events, such as Formula 1 or football matches Kaman seeks to increase sign-up rates and usage of its reusable containers by partnering with more restaurants, offices, food delivery services and event venues, across various cities.",This project partners with high traffic food service venues and delivery services to reduce single-use plastic consumption and waste via a reusable plastic 'lunchbox' system in Japan.,,Kaman,"[""35.66934974289823000"",""139.69243880130335000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
d2bda9e8-f1e7-426f-811f-92bbe4f820ba,J222,POOL Recycling System Japan,ACTIVE,AEPW,Japan,Tokyo,PUBLISHED,"Recotech has established a 'POOL' system in Tokyo, whereby flexible film plastic waste and/or packaging is collected from participating brands and retailers in Japan for recycling into a recycled resin product. They have also developed a mobile 'POOL' application ('POOL App'), which provides end-to-end traceability of plastic waste deposited into the 'POOL' system. Project Objective The project will support the expansion of Recotech's POOL Recycling System with grant funding of US, targeting the collection and recycling of up to 14KT of post-consumer flexible film plastic waste per annum by 2026 (4KT in 2023, 5 KT in 2024, 11 KT in 2025, and 14 KT in 2026). Approach The project intends to replicate and expand Recotech's existing 'POOL' system to five additional sites across Japan, namely: Kanto, Kansai, Nagoya, Fukuoka and Sapporo, as well as to upgrade and expand the features on the POOL App. As part of its expansion to the additional sites, Recotech shall purchase equipment such as compression machines and digital floor scales to be installed at each site. Third party vendors will also be engaged to upgrade and further develop the POOL App.",Recotech targets the collection and recycling of post-consumer flexible film plastic waste into a recycled resin product using their POOL Recycling System across multiple cities in Japan.,,Recotech,"[""35.68654051887047000"",""139.76597285435386000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
e3b2c84f-f7c6-4e5d-8df8-e35a0e4fe505,A003C-GC,PCR-AR,ACTIVE,AEPW,Argentina,Buenos Aires,PUBLISHED,"The City of Buenos Aires (CABA) collects ~200 tons per day of correctly separated, recyclable waste from citizens and businesses, ~50 tons / day of which is plastics (~18,000 tons per year). Between ~3,000-8,000 tons per year (20-40%) of plastic materials arriving at the 16 sorting centers of the city are rejected and sent to landfill. The majority of these rejected materials are low value plastics (e.g., PP, LDPE, PS) that could be recycled. The project provides funding to subsidize the separation of 900-2500 tons of plastic waste that is sold to a recycler in Argentina starting with a pilot of two sorting centers, with the intent of expanding to all 16 sorting centers in the city.  The strategic objectives of this project include: 1.      Demonstrating proof of concept for collection of low-value plastics. 2.     Demonstrating replicability of concept to other sorting centers in Argentina.  3.     Better understanding the economics of supply costs vs. what buyers are able to pay to drive a sustainable market for the low-value plastics.",This project will get more Post Consumer Resin (PCR) into the plastics value chain by creating markets for low-value and contaminated plastics that are going to Argentinian landfill(s).,,Delterra,"[""-34.58305760105133000"",""-58.38262016494386000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
93084f2c-8493-474a-ba6b-8a3a4cfc4aa6,K105-GC,Recycling Hard-to-Recycle Plastics at Scale,COMPLETED,AEPW,Kenya,Nairobi,PUBLISHED,"Introduction The project consists of the expansion of Recipient's existing operations at Dandora landfill in Nairobi, Kenya, and is targeted for completion within eight months. As part of the Project, an additional 600 tons of thermoformed PP and PET hard-to-recycle rigid plastics, and 350 tons of HDPE, PP and LDPE hard-to-recycle flexible plastics will be sourced through the rental and usage of a buy-back and waste sorting center, hiring additional staff, collaboration with waste pickers at the Landfill. Collected plastic waste will be either shredded on-site at the Landfill (i.e. thermoformed plastics), or baled for shipment to Recipient's main facility at Ehotia (' Ehotia Facility ') for transformation into pellets (i.e. flexible plastics). Project Objectives The objectives of the Project are as follows: Collection of (a) 600 tons of thermoformed PP and PET hard-to-recycle rigid plastics, and (b) 350 tons of HDPE, PP and LDPE hard-to-recycle flexible plastics by Recipient's contractors at the Landfill;   Sorting of plastic waste by Recipient at Sorting Center; and  Shipment of collected and sorted waste to Ehotia Facility for further processing,","This project expands Taka Taka Solution's existing waste management efforts in Nairobi, Kenya, collecting and processing hard-to-recycle plastics, diverting them from unmanaged landfills.",,Taka Taka Solutions,"[""-1.24792248626328870"",""36.89640279812057000""]",ESTIMATE,Duplicate (child project of K105),,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
9b663fc8-4dcc-4e50-bff9-2e405f4bb8bf,,Let's Transform,ACTIVE,AEPW,India,Delhi; Ghaziaba; Pandurna; Cochin ; Coimbatore,PUBLISHED,"Saahas Zero Waste (SZW) is a social enterprise that provides end to end waste management services. SZW is working to bring about environmental and social change based on the principles of circular economy and global commitment to Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). The starting point for this early impact project is a social inclusion programme for the informal sector working with waste. This includes waste aggregators and scrap dealers. Collectively, this community and its value chain manages more than 90% of the country's waste. One of the key attributes of this project is to demonstrate an approach where micro-entrepreneurs who work within the informal sector now have access to financial as well as managerial support so that they can have a formalized healthy business. In this project, we will work with 4 micro-entrepreneurs in the National Capital Region (Delhi-NCR), Bangalore (in Karnataka), Pandhurna (in Madhya Pradesh) and Cochin (in Kerala) to collect and process mostly low value plastic waste.",Diversion of mostly low value plastic waste from the environment for co-processing in cement kilns/ recycling and social inclusion of informal sector entrepreneurs.,,Saahas Waste Management Pte Ltd,"[""12.98457033829969700"",""77.58553226245394000""]",ESTIMATE,"Bangalore, Delhi and Pandhurna",,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
3cca7755-f91b-4e87-8de9-b3d0b4d11df0,K114-GC,Prayaash: Strengthening Waste Workers for Zero Waste Nepal,ACTIVE,AEPW,Nepal,Bagmati; Madesh; other,PUBLISHED,"Plastic waste recovery in Nepal is restricted due to the challenging geographical terrain and limited access to necessary infrastructure for collection and transfer. CREASION has undertaken market research in Kathmandu Valley and Chitwan to identify areas in Nepal for collection and recovery of waste PET and other types of plastic. Due to lack of necessary infrastructure for collection and recycling of plastic waste, PET and other types of plastic in remote areas are either burned or become litter in the environment. The outcome of the market research study will enable Creasion to identify and provide solutions to address the plastic waste mismanagement issue in the untapped areas. The project has identified solutions to increase the capacity of existing plastic waste recovery equipment, and recover waste PET as well as other types of plastic. The project will be conducted in two major provinces of Nepal: Bagmati and Madhesh. The project intends to leverage on the existing plastic waste collection infrastructure and informal plastic waste collection network to meet the project objectives. They also intend to expand the said network by creating jobs and additional plastic waste collection opportunities. Since its inception in 2005, Creasion has been working as one of the sector leaders in waste plastic recycling and management in Nepal. Creasion is a key partner of Coca Cola in Nepal for their PET collection project. Possibility to partner with WEIGO / Global Alliance of Waste Pickers to bring technical guidance on social inclusion for the informal sector collectors and sorters is also being explored.",The project targets the collection and recycling of 2.7 kt of plastic waste within two years ; and expanding informal plastic waste collection network to establish a formal waste management system.,,Creasion Ventures Inc Pvt Ltd,"[""27.73151294206030200"",""85.33085480153257000""]",ESTIMATE,Kathmandu,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
928b1cc4-a40d-4d49-b492-2f09857f2f18,K108-GC,SEArcular Ocean Bound Plastic,COMPLETED,AEPW,Indonesia,Gresik,PUBLISHED,"As the first ocean-bound plastic (OBP) recycler in Indonesia, GREENCORE has helped prevent thousands of tons of waste plastic from entering the ocean each year. Now, it looks to reduce the leakage of flexible plastic waste into the environment through a new recycling program that targets waste pickers and junk shops to collect flexible packaging plastic waste (FPPW) along Indonesian coastal areas. Project Objectives Aim to prevent at least 700 tons of FPPW from entering the ocean and instead turn them into high-quality ocean bound certified rLDPE/rLLDPE for circular applications within the first year (7 months from June 2022 to December 2022) Eventually prevent and recycle over 1,200 tons in 2023 and at least the same amount in the subsequent years to come Approach Provide working capital to collection centers ("" pengepul "") in OBP areas to finance the collection of the new stream (FPPW) as compared to their current collection of PET bottles",Mechanical recycling of flexible ocean bound plastics,,Greencore Resources Pte Ltd,"[""-7.38300101458137500"",""112.57727809549866000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
25fa0153-9da6-4243-abf1-0997358df7b0,K018,Flex Film Circularity,ACTIVE,AEPW,United States,"Birdsboro, Pennsylvania",PUBLISHED,"The two main goals of the Flex Film Circularity (FFC) project are to: Address the greater flexible film recycling ecosystem and demonstrate that it is indeed possible to collect flexibles from households curbside, process the single-stream of recyclables (including the flexibles mixed in) at a MRF, and sell the rFlex bale to end markets. Capture best practices to lay the groundwork for scaling to additional communities. The full scale FFC project addresses the greater recycling ecosystem and acts as a pilot City Flagship project focused on three different areas: Community Engagement The plan is to increase the number of households participating in curbside collection of flexible films by introducing the program to new communities, providing education to existing communities participating in the program to increase participation rates, and transition communities using smaller household collections bins to larger rolling carts to capture more recyclables. Sorting at MRF We are currently working with the TotalRecycle MRF operated by J.P. Mascaro & Sons (an operator with proven ability to recycle plastic films and flexible plastics) in Birdsboro, PA. As a part of the original MRFF project, a bolt-on operation was installed in TotalRecycle's existing MRF to sort flexible film from single stream recyclables. The goal of our project is to reduce contamination and improve the quality of the rFLEX bale being produced at TotalRecycle so we can attract more end markets. Further MRF optimizations are needed to improve the quality of the bale. End Markets for the rFLEX bale Only one end market exists today that can take the rFLEX bale as-is. That end market is Kelly Green, located in Waterbury, CT. Kelly Green manufacturers roofing boards made from 100% recycled material including flexible films, beverage cartons, cups and their components in a zero waste, zero water process. They have an existing customer base sufficient to absorb all of their current production capacity. Dry washing, or other types of secondary sort technologies will also be tested as a part of this project to remove fiber contamination and further improve the quality of the rFLEX bale to attract additional end markets. Project History The Alliance has contracted The Recycling Partnership (TRP) to execute/manage the project on the Alliance's behalf. The FFC project builds upon on a previous project, the Materials Recovery Facility of the Future (MRFF) project which preceded the Alliance. The Alliance's Flex Film Circularity (FFC) project has been funded in three different phases. Feasibility study: The FFC project started with a feasibility study performed by TRP to further scope out what a full scale project would look like, focusing on the 3 different areas mentioned above. Total funding of ,000. The feasibility study was successfully completed in the first half of 2022. Booster: In the feasibility study, a MRF optimization opportunity was identified which included purchasing of air stabilizers to help improve the sortation on the conveyor belts. There were long lead times associated with the ordering of these air stabilizers, so the Alliance approved booster funding to be able to place an order for these air stabilizers while the full-scale FFC project scope was going through the approval process. The intention of this booster funding was to speed of the delivery of the equipment and avoid this equipment delivery becoming the bottleneck of the project. Total funding: ,000. Full-scale project: Focuses on the 3 areas and their respective scopes mentioned above. Total funding: .2 million. Expected impact Additional plastic collected as a part of the community engagement increase in participation: 0.3 KTA (Plastic only), additional non-plastic recyclables not captured here Increase in MRF processing capabilities: 1.6-2 KTA Additional end market capacity: 0.9 KTA","A project to demonstrate economically viable recycling of flexible films, in a North American context, based on single stream curbside collection.",,The Recycling Partnership,"[""40.26454461503125500"",""-75.80471073046905000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
4e14d27f-a98a-49e8-af8a-d9f2d0a82103,O006,Sustainability Open Innovation Challenge 2021,COMPLETED,AEPW,Singapore,Singapore,PUBLISHED,"This is an Open innovation challenge for sustainability hosted by ESG (Enterprise Singapore) with the Alliance to End Plastic Waste participating as the challenge provider. The solution providers are invited to develop and present a pragmatic prototype within a cost budget that can be easily deployed to improve the sorting process in a recycling infrastructure. The two challenges are: 1. Development of a low-cost & drop-in manual or semi-automated sorting line for sorting recyclable material from mixed household waste. 2. Development of a proof of concept (PoC) to utilize advanced detection systems improving the quality of sorted plastic fractions obtained from a mixed plastic waste stream. The Alliance to End Plastic Waste together with member company representatives participated in the initial screening of all the submissions then proceeding to online mentoring sessions with the shortlisted candidates. The final candidates will go through clarification phase to fine tune their ideas and presentation before the final pitch day where the winner will be chosen. Project Objective The objective of the Sustainability Open Innovation Challenge is to identify the most relevant innovative solution provider in addressing the sorting issue in the waste management space. Approach Phase 1 Application - Market challenge to companies across the world - Creation of scoring rubric, deliverables for participants Phase 2 Shortlisting - Pre-filtering by agorize - Online voting for pre-screened projects - Online mentoring for shortlisted companies Phase 3 Selection - Organise pitching day for finalists",The Alliance was invited to participate in the Sustainability Open Innovation Challenge sponsored by Enterprise Singapore.,,Enterprise Singapore,"[""1.30690872852526830"",""103.85689135710278000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
877da206-d56e-4273-b7d0-6033330204cd,J227,Transforming plastic waste into beautiful products,ACTIVE,AEPW,Vietnam,"Ho Chi Min City, Vietnam",DRAFT,"Plastic People was part of the top 5 in the Plastic Waste to Value Innovation Challenge undertaken with GPAP, AEPW and WEF. Plastic People reached out to AEPW to ask for co-funding support for expansion of their plant capacity.
Objectives: Reduce unmanaged waste and capturing value by transforming hard to recycle plastic waste into beautiful products.
New capacity built designed for 1.8 KTA.
Enable the ecosystem through education to create awareness in communities, engaging new partners
Mobilize capital with co-funding
Create social benefit by jobs creation, improving the livelihoods of informal collectors and working with social enterprise to develop social housing made of waste plastic panels
Approach:
New factory to be rent and new machinery to be purchased and installed, new capacity to be built.
New job to be created to serve the new factory.
Long term contract with supplier to motivate the education and collection of the communities.
Long term contract to be signed with off-taker.
Stainable business model to attack more market player to provide co-funding for further scale up.","The project converts mixed hard to recycle plastic waste diverted from the environment into high quality products which can be used for furniture, interior design, and construction.",,,"[""10.82000715041708500"",""106.62478334938127000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
39a4157f-49dc-44a1-9c91-e21522740ee7,K118-GC,Fuel from low value plastic waste,ACTIVE,AEPW,Philippines,Quezon City,PUBLISHED,"This project collects and recovers primarily low value flexibles plastic waste in Metro Manila, South and Central Luzon, in the Philippines. Such plastic waste is processed at a facility in Quezon City, with the assistance of second hand shredders to be deployed in various collection areas such as Antipolo, Rizal and South Luzon. The Quezon City facility consists of systemized waste sorting and segregation equipment to produce Refuse Derived Fuel (RDF) of consistent quality. The Project Partner will partner with local governmental units (LGUs), small administrative divisions (barangays), junk shop and other sources of plastic waste. In addition, the project plans to develop a scheme to support and incentivize waste pickers and collectors to collect low value plastic waste. The collection scheme also aims to educate and uplift the livelihoods of such individuals.","The Project consists of collection, aggregation, and processing of low value plastic waste into RDF for co-processing, diverting waste from landfills, water bodies, and the environment.",,Greencycle,"[""14.67528621309938000"",""121.05428905890861000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
c2f95e21-1a8d-42a2-86ea-7d940f87c5ee,J221-GC,Recycling Heroes,COMPLETED,AEPW,Singapore,Singapore,PUBLISHED,"In spite of multiple recycling efforts and initiatives in Singapore, these programmes are more than often fragmentedly segmented with little reach. In addition, the reliance on a singular motivated recycler archetype has given way to unmotivating mechanics, rendering plastic recycling programmes in Singapore relatively ineffective. ESA has identified an opportunity to change this by focusing on a clearly defined segment, school going kids aged 7-16, to influence from young and increase national recycling rates over the next 5-10 years by using a new system of collection, engagement and leadership in schools. Project Objectives By 2023, the project aims to: Engage at least 15,000 students across participating schools with each student contributing clean household plastic waste to the school collection points Target approximately 6 MT of non-contaminated waste plastics sent for recycling Value chain partners continuing to support the program to replicate and scale Approach Collection program for students to recycle clean, source segregated household rigid plastic waste Leadership engagement program in which appointed recycling ambassadors are accountable for collection targets and have opportunities to meet with industry leaders, players, influencers and innovators Mobile app to track waste collection, leadership board (among schools) and provide educational insight into sustainable living tips Click to watch our animated explainer on the project","Recycling Heroes aims to increase plastic recycling in Singapore by engaging primary and secondary schools. This is a student led initiative to collect clean, sort recyclable plastics.",,Environmental Solutions (Asia) Pte Ltd,"[""1.32704077693183380"",""103.63324808439903000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
fc97909d-ea5a-4416-9a28-e53a7a5a09d5,P001,MV XPress Pearl Clean-Up,COMPLETED,AEPW,Sri Lanka,Sri Lanka,PUBLISHED,"Over 240 kilometres of shoreline was polluted by lentil-sized plastic pellets, or nurdles, in the aftermath of a cargo ship fire that happened off the coast of Colombo, Sri Lanka, in May 2021. The ecological disaster is deemed to be one of the worst in the country's history, and experts say recovery could take years. The Alliance saw the opportunity to help and engaged via the Sri Lankan Embassy in Singapore to donate 8 versatile beach cleaning machines (Sweepy) produced by BeachTech in Germany. The machines utilise a mesh that can efficiently sieve out plastic pellets. Project Objectives  Cleanup beach of debris in a timely manner before the beginning of the monsoon season in September Having fewer people clean the beach to reduce the risk of COVID-19 infection Decrease the need for cleaners to have physical contact with potentially harmful debris Approach Donation of 8 BeachTech Sweepy Hydro machines to the Sri Lankan Government. Each machine can separate nurdles from 4,000 square metres and collect up to 250,000 nurdles each day. Watch the Clean-up Highlights Click on the images to watch the videos.","The Alliance donated, through the Sri Lankan Embassy in Singapore, 8 versatile beach cleaning machines (Sweepy) produced by BeachTech in Germany.",,Sri Lanka Marine Environment Protection Authority (MEPA),"[""6.92668078347241250"",""79.86054188470196000""]",ESTIMATE,"Coast of Colombo, Sri Lanka",,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
d47b5e5f-623b-4d28-8471-c6284314422d,J020A,Boosting Cidades+ Participation,ACTIVE,AEPW,Brazil,Guaxupé,PUBLISHED,"This is the first joint project in the global Alliance to End Plastic Waste portfolo which bring together two existing project partners with complimentary skill sets to achieve a common goal. The two project partners involved in this project are Recicleiros and Delterra. The Alliance is currently funding Recicleiros's Cidades+ project, which has a project scope of setting up 20 sorting centers in cities throughout Brazil to complete the first wave of 20 sorting centers towards Recicleiros's goal of reaching 60 sorting centers by 2027. The Alliance has funded two projects for Delterra in Argentina, GIRO and PCR-AR. GIRO is focused on bringing a 3-stream (recyclables, compostables, and mixed waste) waste collection program to the city of Olavarría (~115K inhabitants, approx. 350km from Buenos Aires) and as part of the project, the Delterra team has developed a robust behavior change model that has already been replicated in Argentina. This project intends to take the behavior change model that Delterra has developed in Olavarría, and apply it in another country with a goal of demonstrating replication of their behavior change program across borders. Delterra is looking to expand into Brazil and this will be their first project in the country. The purpose of this project is to apply the Delterra behavior change program in the city of Guaxupé, where there is an existing Recicleiros sorting center in operation today. Currently the Guaxupé sorting center is experiencing lower than expected participation rates of ~7%, which at this pace will extend the breakeven point of this sorting center past the target 5-year breakeven point. Delterra estimates that a 25-30% recycling rate is achieveable with a successful roll-out of their behavior change program. In addition, Delterra will test and adapt their behavior change program to be easily replicated in Brazil and train Recicleiros staff to be able to roll-out this out to their other sorting centers. Project Objective Demonstrate replication of Delterra's behavior change program in Argentina and test applicability in another country, Brazil. Identify the best activation blueprint for small to medium-sized cities in Brazil and create a behavior change model that can be rolled out to other Recicleiros sorting centers to help increase the quality and quantity of recyclables being collected door-to-door in each city. Bring together two different existing AEPW project partners, Recicleiros and Deleterra, with complementary skill sets and strengths. These partners will be able to share best practices and learnings with one another, and partner for success. Increase recycling rates in the city of Guaxupé from 7% to a target of 25- 30%, equating to 300 tonnes/year of plastic recyclables (950 tonnes/year including all recyclables like paper, glass, etc.) ","Recicleiros and Delterra will work together to boost recycling participation rates in the city of Guaxupé (population 55,000 inhabitants), Brazil, where Recicleiros has a sorting facility in operation today.",,Recicleiros; Delterra,"[""-21.30488929120521400"",""-46.70833342711003400""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
1a92cba0-4b30-45ca-a407-f30078075bb7,J230,Plastic Waste Recyclables to Circularity,ACTIVE,AEPW,Malaysia,Malaysia,SUBMITTED,"SmartSkrap, developed in collaboration with CapGemini, enhances the digital traceability of plastic waste while promoting circularity in the value chain by incentivising and mobilising consumers to sort recyclable waste and arrange for collections. With this, the project: (1) Reduces unmanaged waste by intercepting 500 tonnes of source-segregated post-consumer recyclable plastic waste from households or businesses (2) Captures value from waste by recycling intercepted waste collected (3) Enables the ecosystem and communities through direct community engagement with the application (4) Creates social benefit by providing residents with improved access to upgraded waste collection and/or recycling",Empower the community with the digital SmartSkrap application to mobilise consumers and increase post-consumer plastic waste collection from households,,Heng Hiap Industries Sdn Bhd,"[""1.45861548037543790"",""103.97329769542510000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
d4292560-e9b8-47d9-be90-97f3c56b4d21,L043,Microwave Pyrolysis,ACTIVE,AEPW,Mexico,Cuautla,PUBLISHED,"Background Greenback is using Enval Microwave Pyrolysis technology in the operation of their first plant located in Cuautla, Mexico. The plant is co-located with a landfill and MRF that supplies a well waste-picked source of feedstock from the Municipal Solid Waste stream. The technology can convert a wide assortment of films and flexibles, including laminated films to pyrolysis oil for reuse as feedstock for new polyolefins. Aluminum from metal laminates is also captured and processed into ingots for resale. Project Objective The project aims to: Process 6 KTA of the most challenging to recycle flexible plastic waste into high quality pyrolysis oil Demonstrate a decentralized, modular chemical recycling solution that can be scaled and replicated for various populations globally Approach AEPW is loaning Greenback US.3M as part of the project to build two 3 KTA capacity lines in Cuautla. Nestle is also a key partner for the Cuautla project, paying a per tonne fee in order to claim a neutralization credit. Building from a full-scale demonstration plant in Alconbury, UK that has been in operation for 8 years, Greenback intends to quickly replicate with additional lines in Cuautla, at other locations in Mexico, and in many countries around the world especially Europe and Asia. Click the image to watch the inauguration video of the Greenback Cuautla plant.","The Microwave Pyrolysis project in Cuautla, Mexico will processe 6 KTA of films and flexible in modularized, microwave pyrolysis plant co-located with a MRF and landfill.",,Greenback Recycling Technologies Ltd,"[""18.78731408448240700"",""-98.91679650440386000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
65ab1619-b39e-4811-aa1a-32829a8158cf,F005A,Boards of Promise,ACTIVE,AEPW,Philippines,Manila,PUBLISHED,"The Plastic Flamingo (PLAF) collects and transforms mixed plastic waste into eco-boards and furniture in the city of Muntinlupa, one of the 17 Local Government Units (LGUs) of Metro Manila, in the Philippines. The Eco-boards consist of two types: Type 1 - 100% soft plastics (50% monolayer LDPE, plastic bags, pouches and 50% MLP) Type 2 - the Premium quality boards (4ft x 8ft) that include 75% HDPE + 25% MLP or LDPE PLAF partners with various entities to collect mixed plastic waste from more than 160 collection points (i.e. communities, junkshops, organizations) in Manila.","Production of Eco Boards, 100% made of mixed plastic waste collected in Manila, Philippines.",,The Plastic Flamingo (PLAF),"[""14.40659515080029300"",""121.04760805600469000""]",ESTIMATE,,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
6d6f3f2d-4bc5-4874-8056-d5c9bc18f1b1,E033,IPPIN Low Value Plastic Waste Challenge,ACTIVE,AEPW,Vietnam,Vietnam,SUBMITTED,"IPPIN through the Plastics Innovation Hub Vietnam aims to provide a platform for collaboration and a testbed for innovation to address key market gaps in plastic circularity through research and technology. IPPIN partners with national science agencies across Vietnam to identify and define critical business challenges, to develop and deploy commercially sustainable solutions.
The Alliance hopes to develop, de-risk and deploy solution models that enables plastic circularity, especially for low value plastic waste. The Plastics Innovation Hub Vietnam facilitates the innovative development of solution models and offers opportunities for future partnerships within the region, enabling the ecosystem.
Approach: Sponsor a IPPIN challenge to support the development and derisking of disruptive technologies through an incubation program","Through Indo Pacific Plastics Innovation Network (IPPIN), in partnership with CSIRO, the Alliance hopes to facilitate the development of solution models to address low-value plastic waste circularity.",,,"[""10.85122148949167100"",""106.58500058641299000""]",ESTIMATE,Ho Chi Minh,,,2024-10-29 09:28:34.98
